<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Ends Bid To Row Across Pacific  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- A lone French oarsman abandoned
his attempt Monday to row across the Pacific Ocean after doctors
sent to give him medical supplies found traces of gangrene in both
his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Le Guen, who set off Feb. 3 from New Zealand's capital,
Wellington, on his 5,580 mile voyage, aiming for Cape Horn, Chile,
was taken on board a container ship with just one-third of his trip
completed, his agent Martin Pinder said.
</P>
<P>
   Le Guen, 52, was found by doctors to be suffering septicemia, or
blood poisoning, and had the beginnings of gangrene in his feet. He
was delirious and too tired to speak, Pinder said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was concerned on Friday when he was unable to speak for any
length of time,'' Pinder said. ''Jo is a very determined person. He
had to decide when he would quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he set off, Le Guen acknowledged the mammoth task ahead
of him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope I can do the job,'' he said before climbing into his
technology-packed nine-yard black craft. ''I'll do my best to take
care of myself, but who knows -- the South Pacific is bigger than
me.''
</P>
<P>
   His boat, called ''keep it blue,'' boasted electric equipment
powered by batteries charged by solar panels and two windmills on
the boat.
</P>
<P>
   As well as high-tech navigation and communications equipment, Le
Guen carried three sets of 9-foot oars, dried food for the duration
of the journey, fresh water and two water purifiers capable of
extracting salt from sea water. Le Guen had estimated it would take
three-and-a-half months of rowing to reach his destination.
</P>
<P>
   No stranger to ocean crossings, the father of five has twice
rowed the Atlantic. On one trip he went solo and on the other he
was in a two-man team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
