<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar remained lower against the yen
Monday morning despite dollar-buying intervention by Japan's
central bank. Tokyo stocks rose at the start of Japan's new fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 105.19 yen in late morning, down 0.09 yen from
late Friday in Tokyo but higher than its late New York level of
102.64 yen on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 208.21
points, or 1.02 percent, to 20,545.53 at the end of the morning
session. On Friday, the average closed down 104.18 points, or 0.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar moved higher compared with its
New York level on Friday after Bank of Japan conducted yen-selling
to buy the greenback during early Tokyo market on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank action came on the heels of the dollar's slip
as low as 102.82 yen early in Tokyo trading, but the intervention
failed to push the dollar above its level late Friday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming Monday's intervention, Zembei Mizoguchi, head of
international bureau with Japan's Finance Ministry, told reporters:
''Proper action was taken ... we're watching markets closely and
will take appropriate steps as needed.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth such dollar-supporting intervention by the
Bank of Japan since the beginning of this year, with the last one
conducted on March 15 in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the central bank's intervention was not immediately
clear.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials have said the yen's rapid appreciation
against the dollar could hurt the nation's nascent economic
recovery by making Japanese exports more expensive abroad, and thus
less competitive.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 100.42 yen, down
from 100.76 yen late Friday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index started Monday nearly
unchanged from Friday's closing level, but prices later moved
higher as investors welcomed the Bank of Japan's intervention in
the currency market.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said expectations remain strong that public and pension
funds, as well as brokerage dealers, will join individual investors
and investment trusts for active purchasing of Japanese stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, news that Japan's Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was
hospitalized Sunday and remains in intensive care had a limited
stock market impact, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   Mild improvements shown by the Bank of Japan's key ''tankan''
quarterly survey of business confidence were already largely
factored in, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   The tankan showed that business confidence at major
manufacturing companies improved for the fifth consecutive quarter,
reflecting growing faith the country is pulling out of its lengthy
economic slump.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 8.91 points, or 0.52 percent, to 1,714.85. The
TOPIX closed down 6.51 points, or 0.38 percent, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond
stood at 1.7750 percent, unchanged from Friday's finish. Its price
remained unchanged at 101.07.
(km-dj)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
