<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sale of Dobbertin Orbiter turns bitter between couple who createdit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   POMPEY, N.Y. (AP) -- Seven years ago, Rick and Karen Dobbertin
were virtually inseparable, cramped inside their homemade
amphibious craft as they attempted to circumnavigate the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The Dobbertin Surface Orbiter, which looks like a rocketship on
wheels, once transported Rick and Karen Dobbertin to 28 countries
and through the Panama Canal during Project Earth Trek.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's landed them in court.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a messy divorce, they're fighting over the
19,000-pound vehicle, which sits in a barn here just south of
Syracuse. The Dobbertins both say they want to sell the Orbiter and
split the profits, as they agreed when they divorced in 1998. But
each says the other has been uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involves charges of thwarted attempts by Rick and a
potential buyer to see the craft, deceit, improper storage fees and
business deals gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the fight took another turn, as Rick, armed with a
court order signed two weeks ago by State Supreme Court Justice
Charles Major, drove to Pompey to try to move the Orbiter from the
storage barn to a car dealer in Syracuse, a neutral site where the
Orbiter was to be displayed.
</P>
<P>
   But Loren Benedict, a friend of Karen's and former manager of
Earth Trek, on Thursday filed a storage lien at the Onondaga County
Clerk's Office. Benedict, who owns the barn, contends Rick and
Karen must pay $9,000 in storage fees before moving the Orbiter
out.
</P>
<P>
   A sheriff's deputy who escorted Rick to the barn Saturday
morning told him he could not pick up the Orbiter and would have to
sort it all out with officials on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm glad we never had kids because I've spent the past 16
months and $5,000 in attorneys' fees just trying to get visitation
rights to a car,'' Rick said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've learned my lesson,'' Karen said. ''I'll never, ever,
ever, ever get married again.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the couple say it's been painful to watch them tear
each other apart.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a real crying shame it's come to this and
continues,'' Ron Yehle said. ''I told Rick two years ago, you
should have backed the Orbiter out of the garage and set fire to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orbiter - a stainless steel milk tanker that Rick spent more
than 14,000 hours converting into an amphibious home on wheels - is
32.5 feet long. The Dobbertins didn't circle the globe in it, but
the Orbiter did carry them over 27,300 land miles and 3,000 ocean
miles, including 38 states.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, the Orbiter sat in or next to the barn.
Rick, an industrial mechanic, contends that after he moved out of
the barn in 1998 Karen and Benedict made it extremely difficult for
him to gain access to the Orbiter so he could market or sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Karen, a decorating designer who lives at the barn, said Rick
has fabricated charges that she was uncooperative because he's
angry that she divorced him.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer she told Rick he needs a police escort to look at
the Orbiter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the police would like to sit around for four or
five hours while I check it over,'' Rick said in a letter to his
lawyer. ''It would also be rather difficult to explain to a
potential buyer why I needed a police escort to just show the
Orbiter.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen said she was concerned about his temper and whether he
might damage it. ''He's volatile and has a really short fuse,'' she
said. ''I have always been very fearful of this man. He's very
angry at me because I divorced him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Rick arranged to have the Orbiter stored at the car
dealer, which would use it in ad campaigns and provide free
storage. Karen vetoed the move. She said storing it outdoors was
too risky.
</P>
<P>
   The Orbiter, which could sell for more than $100,000, is the
only thing of value remaining from their marriage, and Karen wants
to protect that investment, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rick said Benedict is trying to get back at him for
suing Benedict last year in a dispute over who should pay for taxes
and repairs that occurred when Rick also was living at the barn.
Benedict won that case in small-claims court.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit seeking a court order to compel Karen to turn
over the Orbiter, Rick said she and Benedict ''are simply utilizing
the demand for storage expenses to intimidate, frustrate and
dissuade'' Rick from his efforts to promote and sell the Orbiter.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's known there were storage fees involved,'' said Benedict,
who acknowledged there's no written contract. ''You're not going to
store this in someone's closet.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Critter Gitters,'' a weekly syndicated educational TV series
targeting kids, last year wanted to feature the Orbiter in at least
two episodes, said spokesman Eric Fuhrman. The program, which is
shown on 111 stations around the country, would have put in a plug
for the Orbiter in the credits.
</P>
<P>
   Karen said the show was only going to be in town for a few
hours, and she couldn't arrange her schedule to accommodate it.
Rick accused Karen of wasting huge exposure for the Orbiter.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I had had access to the Orbiter ... 'Critter Gitters' would
have seen it,'' Rick said. ''I'd break my neck to publicize it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I make myself available all the time,'' Karen said. ''Believe
me, I want nothing more than to see this thing go down the road in
somebody else's hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
