<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trail Blazers 95, SuperSonics 82  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Steve Smith scored 21 points and Scottie
Pippen had 18 as the Portland Trail Blazers pulled away to defeat
the Seattle SuperSonics 95-82 Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bonzi Wells added 16 points and hit two big fourth-quarter
3-pointers for the Blazers, who won all four games against the
Sonics this season to sweep them for the first time since 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton had 21 points and 11 assists, and Rashard Lewis
added 18 points for the Sonics, who fell 1{ games behind Sacramento
for the No. 7 spot in the Western Conference playoff race. With
nine games left, Seattle is facing a first-round series against the
Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Portland had to spread around the offense without leading scorer
Rasheed Wallace, who set an NBA record for technical fouls in a
season when he was ejected early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was issued two technicals in succession by referee Joey
Crawford with 10:37 left in the quarter, resulting in Wallace's
sixth ejection of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's 34 technicals break the mark of 32 held by Charles
Barkley and Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   A layup by Payton cut Portland's lead to 67-63 early in the
fourth quarter, but Brian Grant hit a short jumper and Wells made a
3-pointer for a 72-63 lead. Two minutes later, Wells hit another 3
to make it 79-67 with 8:07 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle couldn't get closer than eight the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Detlef Schrempf added 16 points and eight rebounds for the
Blazers, and Damon Stoudamire had eight points, six rebounds and
six assists.
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker scored 16 points for the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers led by two at halftime and used an 11-2 run to get
some breathing room. A fierce two-handed slam by Jermaine O'Neal on
a long lob pass from Smith gave Portland a 62-49 lead, but the
Blazers then went over 5 minutes without a basket.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Maxwell hit 3-pointers to begin and end a 12-3 spurt, and
in between the Sonics hit five straight free throws after starting
8-for-17. That helped Seattle cut the lead to 67-61 after three.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers started the game by missing 14 of their first 17
shots, and the Sonics got a few easy baskets off long rebounds. A
3-pointer by Lewis capped a 10-0 run and put Seattle ahead 16-10
before the Blazers came back to take a 19-18 lead entering the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers went up by seven on a drive by Stoudamire with 3:24
left in the period, but the Sonics rallied to get within 45-43 at
the half.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Blazers center Arvydas Sabonis was at the arena for the
first time since going on the injured list March 24 with a sprained
right foot. He said he hopes to resume practicing next week, but
the team may rest him until the playoffs. ... Baker has hit double
figures in rebounds only twice in his last 29 games. ... Seattle
had 13 offensive rebounds, but none in the second half. ...
Portland's reserves, led by Wells and Schrempf, outscored Seattle's
43-29. In the four games between the teams, the Blazers had a
141-101 lead in that department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
