<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PM-CT--Treasurer Corruption, Conn Bjt, 480  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- George Gomes, a former assistant state
treasurer and key associate of former state Treasurer Paul J.
Silvester, is expected to appear in U.S. District Court today, The
Hartford Courant reported.
</P>
<P>
   Citing sources it did not identify, The Courant reported that
Gomes has been cooperating secretly with federal prosecutors
investigating corruption during Silvester's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for U.S. Attorney Stephen C. Robinson, whose
office is handling the case, would not comment; nor would Gomes'
lawyer-- H. James Pickerstein, a former assistant U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes could not be reached for comment. A message was left at
his Middlebury home by The Associated Press. He has said repeatedly
that he will not comment on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 23, Silvester, his brother, and brother-in-law pleaded
guilty to federal charges stemming from a multi-million-dollar
racketeering and kickback conspiracy from mid-1997 to January 1999.
Since that time, Gomes' name has come up twice.
</P>
<P>
   Silvester, his brother Mark, and brother-in-law Peter Hirschl
were scheduled originally to be sentenced on March 20, but they
were rescheduled for June 19 to allow investigators more time to
bring charges, potentially, against additional defendants. The
three have agreed to testify against others.
</P>
<P>
   Since at least last summer, federal investigators have been
investigating Gomes' hiring in early 1999 as a lobbyist with the
New London law firm of Glenn T. Carberry, a former Republican
congressional candidate with close political ties to Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes worked as assistant treasurer until Silvester lost the
1998 election and left office, with his appointees, on Jan. 6,
1999. Silvester tried to find jobs for a number of his displaced
appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Late in his term, Silvester gave a $27.5-million state pension
deal to Philadelphia-based Keystone Venture Capital Management Co.,
which Carberry had represented in talks with Silvester's office.
Keystone agreed to make payments totaling $275,000-- 1 percent of
the investment-- to Carberry's firm for lobbying services through
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Carberry denies any relation between Silvester's approving the
Keystone deal and his firm's hiring Gomes. Gomes has left the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes' name also came up last fall by J. Vincent Chase, the man
Rowland picked to become state treasurer in mid-1997 and then
dumped a few days later in favor of Silvester.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said that Gomes approached him with the idea of using the
treasurer's office as a 1998 campaign fund-raising machine for
Rowland and the state Republican Party. Chase thought his refusal
to go along with that idea contributed to his not becoming
treasurer. Rowland denied the charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-03-00 0057 </TRAILER>
