<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harvard Names First Radcliffe Dean  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- A leading historian of the Civil War and
the American South will lead the institute created by last fall's
merger of Radcliffe College with Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Gilpin Faust, a history professor at the University of
Pennsylvania, will become the first dean of the Radcliffe Institute
for Advanced Study at Harvard, Harvard President Neil Rudenstine
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The institute was created by the October merger, which ended the
onetime women's school as a separate college after 120 years.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars pursue advanced work in academics, professions and
creative arts at the institute, which maintains a strong commitment
to the study of women, gender and society.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am deeply honored to have been chosen for what seems to be
the most exciting job in higher education,'' Faust said. ''The
institute will build upon Radcliffe's twin traditions of academic
excellence and commitment to women.''
</P>
<P>
   Faust will continue teaching at University of Pennsylvania
through the fall semester and will take over as dean on Jan. 1.
Mary Maples Dunn, former president of Smith College, has served as
acting dean since the merger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
