<HEADLINE> Plane Makes Emergency Landing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- An American Airlines passenger plane made an
emergency landing Sunday night after a loud bang occurred on board.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Rader, spokeswoman for the Fort Worth-based airline, said
she assumed that some of the 57 passengers reported seeing sparks
from the McDonnell-Douglas Super 80's right engine.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 57 passengers also reported seeing sparks from the
right engine, said Andrea Rader, spokeswoman for the Fort
Worth-based airline.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 772 left Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport at 8:25
p.m. en route to LaGuardia Airport in New York. After the captain
heard the bang and saw a warning light go on, he shut down the
right engine and made an emergency landing in Shreveport, La., at
9:20 p.m., Rader said.
</P>
<P>
   It's unknown what caused the loud noise. All the passengers and
the six crew members got off the plane without injuries, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another plane went to Shreveport to pick up the passengers and
take them to LaGuardia, Rader said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was taken out of service and will be inspected Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
