<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Tones Down Message in Nev.  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- A subdued President Clinton took to the
fund-raising trail again Sunday, abandoning white-hot criticism of
his wife's Republican Senate opponent and casting attacks on the
GOP in general economic terms.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to a fund-raiser in Washington Saturday, where
Clinton lambasted New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as a tool of the
''right-wing venom machine,'' Clinton told about 30 people at a Las
Vegas brunch that this fall's election boils down to what each
party plans to do with the federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said voters must choose between the short-term
gratification of an outsized Republican tax cut or the long-term
satisfaction of knowing the money will keep safety-net programs
like Medicare and Social Security in the black for another
generation of retiring Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a moment for making tomorrows. This is not a moment
for indulging ourselves in all this good stuff that's going on
today,'' Clinton said. ''Are we going to pick leaders that we know
understand the future and can take us there, or are we going to
pick people who say things we like to hear and may make things
easier for a month or two?''
</P>
<P>
   The president was the headliner at two events in Las Vegas that
were expected to bring in $525,000 for the Democratic National
Committee. He then headed to San Jose, Calif., site of a $1 million
fund-raiser for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't let this election be about little things. And don't let
this election be about divisive things,'' Clinton said at the San
Jose event. ''We've got the chance of a lifetime to build the
future of our dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   DNC General Chairman Ed Rendell urged donors to keep the money
flowing, saying the Republican National Committee has historically
raked in more soft money donations -- even in 1996 and 1998, when
Democrats won.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are going to outspend us,'' Rendell said. ''We need
enough money to get our message across. We don't have to match 'em
dollar for dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton delivered his remarks Sunday in a voice that bordered on
a whisper at times. He restated his allegiance to Vice President Al
Gore and said his reasons are ''quite apart from my personal
loyalty to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I know that he understands the future and has the knowledge
and experience and the strength to take us there,'' Clinton said.
''And that swamps every one of the specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton mentioned Gore by name, he did not do the same for
the likely Republican candidate, Texas Gov. George Bush. He limited
his comments to the GOP-backed proposal to devote a share of the
federal surplus to a tax-relief package of up to $240 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''For it to become law would mean we could not get the country
out of debt,'' Clinton said. ''All of you would be better off, but
only for a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ''President Clinton and Al Gore consider giving working families
tax relief a risky scheme. Republicans consider it good policy,''
said Chris Paulitz, spokesman for the Republican National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Paulitz said most Republicans are amused that Clinton says the
country lacks the money to give families relief but can find
millions of dollars ''for gallivanting around the world and getting
nothing accomplished.'' Paulitz said he was referring specifically
to Clinton's recent trip to India, Pakistan and Geneva where he
sought to lessen tensions between India and Pakistan and broker
peace between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's brunch was at the home of real estate developer Brian
Greenspun, also publisher of the Las Vegas Sun newspaper and
Clinton's classmate from Georgetown University. Greenspun thanked
Clinton for promising to veto a bill, passed by Congress nearly two
weeks ago, that would allow tons of radioactive nuclear waste to be
shipped to the Nevada desert.
</P>
<P>
   On the flight from Washington, Clinton recalled that Greenspun
was on Georgetown's golf team. Then he went into a discourse about
Robert Trent Jones Sr., the golf course designer whose latest
creation opened this weekend in Las Vegas. Later, he golfed there
with Jones and his son.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's limousine broke down en route to the golf course.
Smoke began billowing out of the car's rear, so the president's
motorcade pulled to a stop on the freeway and Clinton climbed into
a limousine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
