<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anna Deavere Smith puts the White House at center stage  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Anna Deavere Smith doesn't need big costume
changes or lots of props to transform herself into someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing simple black slacks and a crisp white shirt, she just
slips on a tie, picks up a coffee cup or grabs a martini glass and
she changes from Abraham Lincoln to George Stephanopoulos, stopping
in between at Anita Hill and Gloria Steinem.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a playwright-performer known for her one-woman shows
about riots in Los Angeles and Brooklyn's Crown Heights, is back
with a thoughtful, provocative play that seeks to shed light on
today's America through a quintessentially American institution --
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In ''House Arrest,'' just opened at the Public Theater, Smith
revives a technique she used to powerful effect in the past. In
just under three hours, alone on stage, she portrays close to 50
real-life characters, re-enacting what they told her in interviews
or -- for those plucked from history -- reciting words they wrote or
said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith hopes to understand the forces that have shaped America by
looking at the men who have led us, from Thomas Jefferson to
William Jefferson Clinton. Sifting through the history of that most
mythologized, most scrutinized American institution, she delves
into issues of privacy, the press, power and race.
</P>
<P>
   After her triumph with ''Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992'' -- about
that city's deadly riots -- Smith went to Washington's Arena Stage
for a new project in the mid-1990s, long before Monica Lewinsky and
Ken Starr forever changed our ideas about the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Its inhabitant, she decided, would make the perfect subject for
the next piece in her series, ''On the Road: A Search for American
Character.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to know, originally, to what extent the president
keeps us together, and to what extent he does not,'' she recalled
in an interview in a bare, spacious Public Theater rehearsal room.
''I think we're living in a time now, more than ever, where it's
difficult to conceive of the one person who can have the one
explanation for how we are, and I wanted to know why that was.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to find the answer with ''House Arrest,'' she sings at
one moment in the drunken Scottish brogue of a 19th century
Jefferson critic and orates the next in the aristocratic Virginian
tones of the third president himself.
</P>
<P>
   Her characters, all real people, also include high-powered
Washington pundits, a rural South Carolina churchgoer and FDR's
longtime cook. She invokes them vividly and verbatim, including
every giggle, pause, and um and uh.
</P>
<P>
   Early versions of ''House Arrest'' were performed in Washington
and Los Angeles with a cast of actors. But in New York it's a
one-woman show -- updated with current events. It runs through April
16 but may be extended and later taken on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 49, spent more than five years developing ''House
Arrest.'' She traveled with Clinton and Bob Dole on the 1996
campaign, interviewed three presidents and some 300 journalists,
scholars, politicians and government aides. With a team of
researchers, she pored through material on Jefferson, Lincoln and
Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   While the play's first half is historical, Act II focuses
entirely on the Clinton presidency -- sex and politics as only
modern Washington can combine them. Smith pursues the theme
suggested by her title, examining the paradox of a man who has
immense power but must live with the pressure of being watched
almost constantly.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're a celebrity culture and the president is the celebrity
in chief,'' Stephanopoulos says in the play, portrayed by Smith
with martini glass in hand. ''The deal is you can do whatever you
want. The price is, everybody's going to know everything you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny has a morbid side. Former U.S. News &AMP; World Report
photographer Brian Palmer -- Smith, in a red baseball cap pulled on
backwards -- tells how White House photographers constantly focus on
the president at public events, just in case disaster strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ''You wanna have the president in your view, in your viewfinder,
pretty much all the time,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what Smith does in a gripping segment that combines
past and present, as she recreates Lincoln's last moments while
training a row of cameras on the doomed president.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can't write a play about privacy in the White
House without Lewinsky and her blue Gap dress.
</P>
<P>
   Smith captures the fervid pursuit of sexual wrongdoing behind
the calm, legalistic face of Starr's investigation by playing one
of his deputies questioning Clinton for a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me define 'phone sex' for the purposes of my question,''
the lawyer says, recalling the complicated language Washington
created for a simple act.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright sees the Lewinsky investigation as the
culmination of a cynicism that began with the Vietnam War and
Watergate and has grown deeper since.
</P>
<P>
   In today's public life, she said, ''There isn't so much a
pursuit of truth as there is a pursuit of lies. The question is,
how will we ever move out of that? ... Spiritually, it breeds a
dreadful, dreadful cynicism.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith hopes theater can help reinvolve Americans in the nation's
future, and bridge divides like the ones around race.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mission of my adult life,'' she explains, ''is how to
cause communication across boundaries of difference, and how to use
art as part of that mission.''
</P>
<P>
   In ''House Arrest,'' Smith traces the nation's racial divides to
its earliest days, musing over Jefferson's internal contradictions
and complicated legacy. The eloquent, intellectual author of the
Declaration of Independence owned slaves, believed black people
were inferior and did little to oppose the spread of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   In the play, he comes to symbolize the moral ambiguity on which
America was founded, and which haunts us today.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, Smith quotes documentary filmmaker Ken Burns as
saying, ''ensured that we would inherit the poison of the
indecision on race.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This idea that Jefferson was living in moral ambiguity every
single day of his life, and that there was a shadow side to
everything he did, is a part of human nature,'' Smith said. ''And
the question is, how do we work with the shadow, how do we keep it
in check?''
</P>
<P>
   Bit by bit, she answers herself, opening one mind at a time,
optimistic that America's deepest wounds can be healed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Slavery was a big mistake, so that seems to me to indicate
that there can also be a big lesson,'' she says. ''I don't know
that I will live to see the great symphony, the sort of Beethoven's
Ninth of America, but I believe that will happen in the next
century, and plan on living whatever time I have left to push that
along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-03-00 0204 </TRAILER>
