<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Gets a Kick Out of Program  </HEADLINE>
By EDDIE PELLS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Football at Florida is a religion. Billy
Donovan is doing his best to make sure it's not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators play Michigan State tonight for the national
basketball championship. If Florida wins, it will become just the
sixth school with national titles in both major men's sports.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the hype over football, the Florida basketball team
would have just as many national championships as the football team
if it beats the Spartans: one.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh, yeah, it's definitely a basketball school now,'' coach
Donovan said sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   ''I came here knowing this is not a basketball school, nor is it
ever going to be a basketball school. All I'm concerned about is
doing the best job I can.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a lot of ground to cover and did it much quicker than
anyone thought possible. At 34, the fast talker from Long Island is
on the verge of becoming the third youngest coach to win a national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   He has done it with a running, 3-point-shooting style of play --
they call it Billy Ball -- that rivals Steve Spurrier's Fun 'N' Gun
as the most exciting offense on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier says he fully supports the basketball team. He'll be at
home tonight, watching the game on TV just like thousands of other
Gators fans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a stark contrast from years past, when the buzz around
Gainesville would have been spring football practice and next
weekend's annual football scrimmage, the Orange and Blue game.
</P>
<P>
   ''Football has always had a big interest in the South,''
Spurrier said. ''As far as basketball goes, when you're hanging NIT
banners in your gym, that says you don't have much of a tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I had no doubt Billy could do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, athletic director Jeremy Foley hired Donovan
away from Marshall. As much as a turnaround, Foley needed a name,
personality and style fans could rally behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''I looked at some of the scores of when Billy was in
Marshall,'' Foley said. ''He lost to Kentucky 120-98. It was a
loss, but at least there's some entertainment value there.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the team began to win, more fans turned out. Many students,
known as the Rowdy Reptiles, spend hours outside the arena before
big games, lining up for prime seats that were empty in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
   Florida averaged 9,783 fans this season, about 3,500 more than
when Donovan arrived.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, longtime Florida fan Patrick Geraghty had
trouble getting tickets for the marquee games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me, that's unbelievable,'' said Geraghty, who drives four
hours from Fort Myers to watch the Gators. ''Next year, I'm
planning on buying season tickets, even if I only go to one or two
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Gators fans wonder how long the success will last. They
also wonder if Donovan will tire of working in Spurrier's shadow,
and leave for a school with more basketball tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Foley gave Donovan a healthy contract extension last year and is
making every effort to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he leaves, it won't be because of petty jealousies,'' Foley
said. ''Steve Spurrier and Billy Donovan get along and work very
well together. We have a very fine football program. We have a very
fine basketball program. I don't see any reason why everyone can't
coexist together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 0214 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000403.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spartans Happy To Run With Florida  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY ATKINS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Michigan State knows how to win at just
about any game: fast, slow, bruising defense, run-and-gun offense.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Florida wants to try in tonight's national championship
game, the Spartans are saying, ''Bring it on.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to be remembered as champions,'' forward A.J. Granger
said Sunday. ''No one remembers who came in second.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans got caught up in an ugly defensive struggle in
their 53-41 win Saturday night over Wisconsin. Tonight, they'll
play an up-tempo game against the high-energy Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Either style is fine with the Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not saying it's not going to be tough and physical against
Florida, but we pretty much can get more up-and-down and try to
play our style of basketball,'' point guard Mateen Cleaves said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the same style Florida favors.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators look more like greyhounds on paper. They averaged
84.1 points during the season and 79.4 points in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spartans are big, fast and athletic, too. They averaged
73.7 points during the season. That's easy to overlook after
watching them play a slow-down team like Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans beat Mississippi State 96-63; Illinois -- a team
very much like Florida -- 91-66; and Michigan 114-63.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think our players are confident that no matter who we play,
we've played somebody like them,'' coach Tom Izzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that is Izzo's doing. He's the one who scheduled
nonconference games against Texas, North Carolina, Kansas, Arizona
and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Spartans believe they should be able to handle
Florida's vaunted press. Other good teams have pressed them -- and
failed.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans beat UConn 85-66. Syracuse, another good pressing
team, led the Spartans by 14 points early in the second half of a
regional semifinal game, but lost by 17.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we match up with Florida very well,'' said forward
Andre Hutson, who handles the low post for Michigan State. ''They
don't have anyone really tall or bigger than we are.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are big physically and very athletic, just like we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State averaged 12 more rebounds a game than opponents
during the season. Florida's margin, by comparison, was 5.4
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rebounding will be a big key, especially because of their
style,'' the 6-foot-8, 240-pound Hutson said. ''We're going to send
four guys to the boards, just like we always do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, this game might be decided the way so many Michigan
State games are decided -- by the play of Cleaves. Forward Morris
Peterson has scored the big points in this tournament, but Cleaves
is still the leader.
</P>
<P>
   It is a role that Cleaves, a three-time All-American, stayed in
school to play.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tell him it's like Deion Sanders,'' Izzo said. ''It's prime
time, and he's a prime-time player. A lot is going to be on his
shoulders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
