<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Even Pete's Grandma Had Game  </HEADLINE>
By JIM LITKE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tough love meant one thing in the Peterson
household and something else on the basketball court. That's where
the women teaching the brash young man to play the game came up
with their motto: Defeat him or die trying.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always felt like if I beat one of them -- at anything -- that
I'd really accomplished something,'' Michigan State's Morris
Peterson recalled on the eve of the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could be opening the window fastest, stepping in the front
door first, anything. Win and you could brag the rest of the day.
That's where I learned to be so competitive. Definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of college basketball has been paying for those lessons
ever since. They began when Morris and Valarie Peterson's youngest
child and only son was a 6-year-old who liked talking trash almost
as much as playing. They ended a half-dozen years after that, when
the women turned Morris over to boys his own age and size.
</P>
<P>
   Both parents coached basketball at nearby middle schools in
Flint, Mich., so even after they divorced in 1983, Morris never
lacked instruction -- or competition. Both of his sisters, Tonda and
Trina, older by five and two years, respectively, were already
budding stars who would play in college.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, in turn, made sure none of them ever lacked motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'd make a shot -- one shot! -- and he'd go on like he was
Muhammad Ali,'' Valarie recalled. ''He'd get up in your eyes and
scream, 'I'm bad! I'm the greatest!' And he wouldn't shut up.
</P>
<P>
   ''And so,'' she added, ''we banded together.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, called Pete by those closest to him, could play. It
was just his bad luck to be born into a family where everyone
could. Even his grandmother, the late Clara Mae Spencer, had game.
What separated her from the other Peterson women is she didn't make
a point of letting Morris know it.
</P>
<P>
   Valarie had no such qualms. When Morris laughed at stories about
how good a player she had been, his sisters arranged a 3-point
shooting contest. Morris made one and missed; Valarie sank five
straight, turned and walked off the court.
</P>
<P>
   ''You should have seen poor Morris,'' Tonda Broom said. ''His
eyes were as big as doughnuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonda went next. In a game to 25 baskets, Morris jumped out to a
23-11 lead. Everything was running smooth until he opened his
mouth. His countenance turns mournful at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ''She pushed me, knocked me down and blocked every one of my
shots after that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tonda was the enforcer, Trina the finesse player. Playing
against both, Peterson learned to bang inside against the
Wisconsins of the world, and hold his own in jump-shooting duels
with run-and-gun outfits like Syracuse. The downside is he was
nearing his 12th birthday before he had a ''W'' over anybody in the
family -- except Clara Mae.
</P>
<P>
   ''And she could have beat him, because she was an athlete,
too,'' Valarie said. ''But she was a softy.''
</P>
<P>
   The bond forged between the old woman and her first grandson was
finally loosened March 25, when Spencer died at 72, a month after a
stroke. Peterson attended her funeral Thursday, but three days
later, he still regretted not making a last visit.
</P>
<P>
   ''She wouldn't mind, because she knew this was his time of
year,'' said Christine Bender Williams, her sister. ''I can say
that, because I feel like I'm representing her. I know if she
could, she'd tell us to go on and do whatever is going to help Pete
take care of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times after he did that in Saturday's semifinal,
Peterson pointed his index finger toward the sky. On the side of
his sneakers, too, he scribbled, ''R.I.P. Clara Mae Spencer.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the games and the practices have provided welcome
distractions. To pass the time between, Peterson relied on teammate
Mateen Cleaves, who grew up playing alongside and against him since
they were 7-year-old prodigies on the Flint playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they put off the NBA draft to return for their senior
seasons. Then they survived a rough stretch last fall when Cleaves,
sidelined with a broken foot, pushed Peterson to assume a greater
leadership role with the Spartans. Now, Cleaves provides Peterson
with the quiet reassurance that Spencer once did.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she was with him out there,'' Cleaves said after
Peterson scored 20 points to beat Wisconsin. ''She carried some of
those shots for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated
Press. Write to him jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
