<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Hockey League Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   One week left and there's still plenty to decide in the NHL
playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal earned a point the hard way Sunday night, losing 6-5 in
overtime at Detroit. The Canadiens rallied from a three-goal hole
and two third-period deficits, only to fall behind the Red Wings
again with only 2:59 left.
</P>
<P>
   But the Canadiens tied it with 1:02 remaining in the third
before Martin Lapointe ended it with 14.4 seconds to go in the
extra session.
</P>
<P>
   ''We play well when we're down. Somehow we have to change
that,'' Montreal forward Brian Savage said. ''But we come out of
Detroit with a point. We're not going to complain about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulation tie was enough to pull Montreal into a
ninth-place tie with Buffalo, just one point behind Carolina, the
current holder of the Eastern Conference's final playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing is it's still in our hands,'' Montreal's Shane
Corson said. ''We still have a heartbeat. That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes jumped back into the key slot with a 1-0 victory
over Philadelphia. Bates Batagglia scored on a breakaway just 1:18
into the game and Arturs Irbe stopped all 31 Flyers shots.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's loss, coupled with New Jersey's 4-1 victory over
Tampa Bay, pushed the Flyers four points behind the Devils in the
Atlantic Division. New Jersey, with 101 points, went over the
100-point mark for the fourth straight season.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils also lead the Washington Capitals by two points for
the top seed in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   In other games, it was St. Louis 4, Ottawa 1; Colorado 3, Dallas
2 in overtime; Atlanta 5, the New York Islanders 4; and Vancouver
3, Chicago 2.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Stevenson scored one of Montreal's three third-period
goals and assisted on another by Martin Rucinsky. Patrice Brisebois
and Savage also scored for the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still alive,'' Canadiens coach Alain Vigneault said.
''It's going to be a tough fight down to the end. It's going to be
a fun week of hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Shanahan scored his 40th goal, Sergei Fedorov had a goal
and an assist and Steve Duchesne also scored for Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Things aren't much clearer in the Western Conference. The Red
Wings' victory kept Detroit three points behind St. Louis for the
conference's top spot.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their backs were against the wall and they needed some
points,'' Detroit coach Scotty Bowman said of the Canadiens. ''They
charged in and things happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado extended its Northwest Division lead over Edmonton to
six points. Vancouver inched within one point of San Jose for the
eighth and final playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
Avalanche 3, Stars 2
</P>
<P>
   Shjon Podein stole the puck from goalie Ed Belfour behind the
net and scored a short-handed goal with 47 seconds left in
overtime, lifting Colorado over visiting Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Roy had 22 saves for his 443rd regular-season victory,
four shy of NHL career leader Terry Sawchuk.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bourque and Adam Deadmarsh also scored for Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull and Sylvain Cote had Dallas goals. Hull scored his
609th career goal, one fewer than his father, Bobby.
</P>
<P>
Hurricanes 1, Flyers 0
</P>
<P>
   Arturs Irbe stopped 31 shots to lead Carolina past Philadelphia
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Irbe set a franchise record with his 32nd victory and recorded
his fifth shutout this season, one shy of his career high.
</P>
<P>
Devils 4, Lightning 1
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Elias had two goals and Martin Brodeur stopped 26 shots
as New Jersey won at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, who tied Terry Sawchuk for the most wins over a
five-year span with 195, lost his shutout when Fredrik Modin scored
with 3:40 left.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Malakhov and Scott Stevens also scored for the Devils.
</P>
<P>
Blues 4, Senators 1
</P>
<P>
   Backup goalie Jamie McLennan stopped 26 shots, and Scott Young
scored twice, leading St. Louis over Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis has won 55 straight when it scores three or more goals
in a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues, who last won a division title in 1987, are 7-1-2 in
their last 10 games. The Senators, who have also clinched a playoff
spot, have lost six of nine.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Turgeon and Todd Reirden also scored for St. Louis, which
beat Ottawa at home for the first time since 1993. Blues defenseman
Al MacInnis played in his 1,200th career game.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa center Radek Bonk scored his 22nd goal.
</P>
<P>
Canucks 3, Blackhawks 2
</P>
<P>
   Denis Pederson had two goals and an assist as Vancouver won at
Chicago. Ed Jovanovski also scored for the Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   Canucks goaltender Felix Potvin stopped 17 shots. He lost a bid
for his second shutout this season with 5:54 left when Bryan McCabe
beat him with a 30-foot shot. Steve Sullivan made it 3-2 with 1:10
left.
</P>
<P>
Thrashers 5, Islanders 4
</P>
<P>
   Donald Audette scored on a third-period breakaway as Atlanta
snapped a 17-game home-winless streak, beating the New York
Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Ferraro had a goal and two assists for the expansion
Thrashers, who were 0-15-2 at Philips Arena since Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, the NHL's worst team, had lost five straight and was
1-16-1 since winning at Colorado on Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, who got two goals from Mike Watt, lost to the
Thrashers for the third time in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta goalie Damian Rhodes, playing his 10th straight game,
stopped 17 shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
