<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shaq's Lakers Dominate Knicks  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Shaquille O'Neal beat up on Patrick Ewing again, Kobe
Bryant vs.
Chris Childs was a draw, and the Los Angeles Lakers just kept
rolling through the regular season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   O'Neal dominated Ewing for the second time in two weeks, scoring
24 of his 34 points in the first half as Los Angeles pounded the
New York Knicks 106-82 to reduce the magic number for clinching
home-court advantage throughout the playoffs to two.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and Childs were ejected following a dust-up with 43.4
seconds left in the third quarter and the Lakers leading 71-60.
</P>
<P>
   Childs appeared to hit Bryant in the neck and upper chest, while
Bryant's punch missed. Neither player was hurt, but both face
automatic suspensions for throwing punches.
</P>
<P>
   On a day of hot tempers, Portland forward Rasheed Wallace set a
single-season record for technical fouls by picking up two in the
Trail Blazers' 95-82 victory over Seattle, while Vancouver coach
Lionel Hollins was ejected in a 100-86 loss to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   In other NBA action Sunday, Phoenix edged Minnesota 87-86,
Sacramento routed Philadelphia 117-95, Detroit pounded New Jersey
113-92, Indiana topped Toronto 104-83, Miami held off San Antonio
88-84, Chicago beat Cleveland 83-74, and Milwaukee beat Golden
State 117-113.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal added 12 rebounds, four assists and five blocked shots in
outplaying Ewing, who is in the twilight of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing shot only 6-of-17 and had 14 points and eight rebounds in
New York's most lopsided loss this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a great player and he played well, that's it,'' Ewing
said of O'Neal. ''The Lakers are the best team in the league and we
feel we're one of the best, but we didn't play like it today.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had 43 points and 10 rebounds when the Lakers beat the
Knicks 92-85 at Madison Square Garden on March 19.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers (62-12) have won nine games in a row and 28 of 29.
They improved to 27-3 against Eastern Conference teams, the best
record by a West team against the East in NBA history. LA finishes
with eight games against Western Conference teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''I give them credit, they're a championship-caliber team,''
Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ''And what they showed us is how
far away we are.''
Trail Blazers 95, SuperSonics 82:
</P>
<P>
   Wallace reached 34 technical fouls for the season -- two more
than the old mark shared by Dennis Rodman and Charles Barkley --
with back-to-back calls early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith scored 21 points as Portland, at home, completed a
season sweep of Seattle for the first time since the 1990-91
season.
Mavericks 100, Grizzlies 86:
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Nowitzki scored 15 of his 22 points in the third quarter to
lead Dallas to its 12th win in its last 19 road games. Mike Bibby
had his first career triple-double for Vancouver, which has lost 16
of 17.
Suns 87, Timberwolves 86:
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Johnson made his return two years after retiring, playing
the entire fourth quarter as visiting Phoenix won its third
straight. Johnson, signed when Jason Kidd broke an ankle, had four
points and two assists.
Kings 117, 76ers 95:
</P>
<P>
   Jason Williams hit four of his five 3-pointers in the third
period as Sacramento broke open a close game with a 13-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   Vlade Divac had 14 points, 11 rebounds and a season-high 11
assists for his sixth career triple-double, and Chris Webber added
26 points, 10 rebounds and eight assists for the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson scored 23 points, six below his average, as the
76ers dropped their third consecutive away game.
Pistons 113, Nets 92:
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Stackhouse scored 34 points, 10 off second-quarter dunks,
as Detroit pounded host New Jersey to avoid falling into eighth
place in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill added 32 points, 12 rebounds and eight assists for
the Pistons, who snapped a two-game losing streak.
Pacers 104, Raptors 83:
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's Vince Carter left the game in the third quarter with a
bruised right shoulder and didn't return. Sam Perkins made all six
of his 3-point attempts and scored a season-high 22 points for
visiting Indiana.
Heat 88, Spurs 84:
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Mashburn scored 26 points and Miami capitalized on Tim
Duncan's poor free-throw shooting for its 16th win in 17 home
games.
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson had 28 points for the Spurs, who had won five
straight. San Antonio's Duncan finished with 19 points, but missed
three of four free throws in the final minutes of the game.
Bulls 83, Cavaliers 74:
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carr scored 10 points in the fourth quarter to spark
Chicago, which ended a 13-game road skid. Elton Brand led Chicago
with 23 points and 14 rebounds.
Bucks 117, Warriors 113:
</P>
<P>
   Sam Cassell scored 31 points and Ray Allen had 27 as visiting
Milwaukee handed Golden State its ninth straight loss.
</P>
