<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hero of the Holocost to be honored  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SALEM, Conn. (AP) -- As a diplomat in France during World War II
, Hiram Bingham IV defied his supervisors' policies and aided
thousands of Jews fleeing Nazi persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland has honored the Salem native by declaring
today Hiram Bingham day in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham sheltered Jews in his diplomatic residence in Marseilles
and helped them obtain visas to escape Nazi-occupied Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''He put humanity before his career,'' his son Robert Bingham
said. ''My father had a sense that Hitler had to be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   For years after his death in 1988 at the age of 85, the Bingham
remained largely unrecognized.
</P>
<P>
   ''He never boasted about his deeds,'' said his son. ''He was a
humble, kind person.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bingham worked to change that. He has launched an effort
for the U.S. Postal Service to issue a stamp honoring his father.
</P>
<P>
   Led by U.S. Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-2nd District, and U.S. Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., more than 60 congressmen and senators
have supported the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Today also marks the opening of an exhibit at U.N. headquarters
in New York honoring Bingham and 10 other diplomats credited with
saving a total of more than 200,000 lives during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is called -- Visas for Life: The Righteous Diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ''In many cases, this will be the first time that the survivors
will have the opportunity to meet the families of their diplomatic
rescuers,'' said Eric Saul, director of the exhibit, which will
remain at U.N. headquarters until April 28.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 members of Bingham's family, including several of
his sons and daughters, were planning to attend the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward with a great deal of zeal to meeting the
survivors,'' Robert Bingham said. ''It's heartwarming knowing my
father played a hand in keeping them alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
