<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aboriginals May Hold Protests  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CORDER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Aboriginal activists threatened today
to hold violent protests at the Sydney 2000 Olympics after
Australia's government said they exaggerated the effects of a
decades-long policy of taking aboriginal children from their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Protests at the Olympics are ''going to be very violent,''
Aboriginal activist Charles Perkins told the British Broadcasting
Corp. in an interview rebroadcast in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are telling all the British people, please, don't come
over. If you want to see burning cars and burning buildings, then
come over,'' Perkins said. ''Enjoy yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins -- one of the main representatives of his community --
later toned down his comments, but when asked about protests, he
told Australia's Channel Nine television: ''It's 'burn, baby, burn'
from now on. Anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Aboriginal Affairs Minister John Herron
suggested that reports of an estimated 100,000 Aboriginal children
taken by authorities between 1910 and the 1970s -- known as the
''stolen generation'' -- were exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ''A generation is all people born around that period. It didn't
affect all Aboriginal people, and that's the point that I'm making
in my'' report on the subject, he told Channel Nine. Portions of
the report appeared in the press Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the policy, children were taken from their families in the
belief that Aborigines were doomed and saving the children was the
only humane alternative. Light-skinned Aboriginal children were
given to white families for adoption, while dark-skinned children
were put in orphanages.
</P>
<P>
   The government says 10 percent of Aborigines were affected by
the policy. It did not say how many people that amounted to.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the Saturday accounts of Herron's report, New South
Wales' 118 Aboriginal land councils voted to march in protest on
Sept. 16, the first day of Olympic competition here.
</P>
<P>
   ''All bets are off,'' Lyall Munro, Olympic protest campaign
delegate to the Metropolitan Aboriginal Land Council, told local
media. ''Aboriginal people will rise up in this country and show
the world how racist Australia is.''
</P>
<P>
   The report and Herron's defense of it have plunged the
relationship between Prime Minister John Howard's government and
Aborigines to an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   In parliament, Howard admitted that the separation of Aboriginal
children from their mothers had been a serious blemish on the
nation's history, but again ruled out a formal apology.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality is that large numbers of children were taken in
circumstances in which they should not have been taken,'' Howard
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted that Herron's submission had been accurate.
</P>
<P>
   News of the report first surfaced when the Daily Telegraph in
Sydney quoted the document as saying, ''There was never a
generation of stolen children.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowitja O'Donoghue, chairwoman of an Aboriginal advisory
committee set up by Sydney Olympics organizers, said Aborigines
should protest at Australia's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it matters not whether it was a generation, (or)
whether it was 10 percent, but the policy was wrong,'' she said.
O'Donoghue was taken from her parents when she was 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Olympics organizers refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leader Kim Beazley said he understood anger at the
government's report, but he said the Olympics should be left alone
by protesters. ''The Olympics ought to be off limits. It ought to
be an occasion of joy for all Australians and a chance to show off
what good hosts we can be,'' Beazley told reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 0304 </TRAILER>
