<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 03:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UConn's Shea Ralph Steals Show  </HEADLINE>
By KEN BERGER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- It's hard to imagine what Shea Ralph would
do without basketball. She plays it like a skydiver making a daring
jump, or a relay runner making that final, exhausting push for the
finish line.
</P>
<P>
   She played for the national championship Sunday night as if the
whole world were trying to take it away from her. And no one takes
anything away from Ralph without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a drive that I have, something that's been taught to me
the hard way,'' said Ralph, who led Connecticut to its second
national championship with a 71-52 victory over archrival
Tennessee. ''Enjoy the moment, and every day, and every minute that
you have in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   This victory was so easy because one player on the court
wouldn't stop diving, swatting, snarling and shouting. With all
this, Ralph somehow found time to get nearly every loose ball, make
every deadeye pass, toss in every layup that her tenacity earned.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph scored 15 points on 7-for-8 shooting and had seven
assists, six steals and a block for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I've ever wanted anything like I wanted this
tonight,'' said Ralph, the MVP of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Most valuable? That was as easy to see as Ralph's pained
expression -- always contorted with a mixture of consternation and
aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ''We came out with a vengeance,'' Ralph said. ''We came out like
we wanted something, and we got it. And I think we deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   After sparking UConn's 21-6 run to start the game, Ralph ensured
there would be no letup in the second half. She started off with a
layup and a double-clutch, driving jumper to make it 36-19, then
picked off a pass and quickly set up Svetlana Abrosimova for a
layup to give the Huskies a 40-19 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shea Ralph is the hustle player of the year on that team,''
Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said. ''She gives them so much energy.
She's a great leader by example.''
</P>
<P>
   She got free for another layup to make it 48-27, then ran a
little give-and-go on the fast break with a bounce pass to
Abrosimova for a layup that gave UConn a 50-27 lead with 13:31
left.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a performance for a player who missed the entire
1997-98 season with her second ACL injury to her right knee in as
many seasons. She blew out her ACL in the Huskies' first game of
the NCAA tournament on March 15, 1997, then did it again on Aug.
29.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were moments of doubt, but I always knew that I would
play again,'' Ralph said. ''I never knew how good I would be. I
never knew what kind of impact I would have on my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph was asked what got her through those dismal months of
rehab, when it seemed her knee would never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's always been the national championship,'' Ralph said.
''It's always been winning the last game of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   When she forced a jump ball, she pumped her fist wildly. When
she attacked the basket for an acrobatic jumper, she screamed,
flexed her biceps and grabbed any teammate who would dare share her
viselike embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're in the position that we were this year, you can't
let that slip through your fingers,'' Ralph said. ''You never know
when you're going to have it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The basketball certainly doesn't slip through Ralph's fingers.
When UConn blitzed Tennessee with a 21-6 run to start the game,
Ralph was in the middle of every scrum. A fan watching basketball
for the first time might have assumed that the goal of No. 33 was
to rub her elbows on every inch of the court -- then get up and
scream like a professional wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, was it effective. Ralph came up with four steals and forced
at least three jump balls in the first half alone. She turned
Tennessee's offensive gameplan into a mosh pit -- with herself in
the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph had three fouls at halftime, but never committed another
one. She was 3-for-4 for seven points, had four steals, a block and
three assists as UConn led 32-19 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, Ralph was one of the first to dive into the ultimate
mosh pit when it was over. She tackled Sue Bird, UConn's little
point guard, as the Huskies celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if I've seen us play this well all year,'' Ralph
said. ''We got the ultimate prize.''
</P>
<P>
   The knee injuries and medical redshirt season have kept her
around Storrs so long that the running joke in women's basketball
is, ''Shea Ralph is still at Connecticut?''
</P>
<P>
   You bet she is. And she's only a junior. She'll be back for more
floorburn next year, and probably can't wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 0306 </TRAILER>
