<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poets Creating Works on Computer  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- It's poetry that cannot occur on paper --
the blending of the most modern technology and an age-old literary
form. It's e-poetry, and there is no turning back now.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic poets around the world are creating works that evolve
and ''perform'' on the computer screen, said Loss Pequeno Glazier,
director of the University at Buffalo's Electronic Poetry Center,
which displays the work of dozens of e-poets.
</P>
<P>
   The center's Web site, he said, logs 8 million visitors a year
from 90 countries. In honor of ''National Poetry Month,'' it will
include a collection of new digital works for and about April.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic poetry has movement or programming qualities that
allow for forms of experimentation that wouldn't even occur to
print poetry writers, Glazier said. Poems may move, talk, change
and interact with the reader.
</P>
<P>
   In Roberto Gilli's ''War,'' for example, changing text is
superimposed over black and white images that flash onto the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kac's ''Uirapuru'' extends the myth of a magical
Amazonian bird and sings to the reader. The work incorporates the
writer's personal mythology into the realm of the rainforest and
transforms the bird into a tele-robotic flying fish that the reader
can manipulate.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic poetry was the logical extension of ''concrete
poetry'' that became popular over the last several decades, where
poets would arrange letters and words in certain shapes, lending a
visual dimension to the work, Glazier said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once people were working with computers, they said how could
we do something on the computer with poetry that can't be done on
paper,'' he said. ''It was at that moment that electronic poetry
was born.''
</P>
<P>
   The new style features kinetic poetry, poetry that moves, and
programmable poetry, in which a computer program actually helps
create the poem.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the Web, you can have the poems move or have some sort of
timing to them or changeability,'' Glazier said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only shapes, but colors, fonts and motion are important
elements of electronic poetry. That means e-poets must be computer
savvy as well as visionary, though there are programs to help
fledgling artists along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Although the poems cannot be bound in a book and put on a
library shelf for the benefit of future generations, they can be
electronically archived and displayed on Web sites like the
Electronic Poetry Center, which was formed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As technology changes and threatens to render the current
programs obsolete, Glazier said the center will do its best to
translate poems into more up-to-date formats so they will be
preserved.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a challenge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://epc.buffalo.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 0313 </TRAILER>
