<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 08:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Isakson Carving Own Identity  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY McMURRAY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Johnny Isakson ranks 433rd of 435 House
members in seniority, but his office is fit for a speaker. It was,
in fact, where one -- Newt Gingrich -- used to conduct his district
business not long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson, a Republican from Marietta, Ga., inherited the
congressional seat and prime office vacated when Gingrich resigned
last year after the GOP's poor election showing in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's old quarters in the Rayburn House Office Building are
large and have a clear view of the Capitol. It's where he conducted
his district business, while using the official speaker's office in
the Capitol for his other duties.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman, Isakson normally would expect to have modest
accommodations. He admits enjoying the spoils of following a
speaker but is quick to say he's no reincarnation of the flamboyant
Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look, I'm not Newt,'' Isakson said. ''My dad taught me a long
time ago that if you can't be a success being yourself, you'll
screw it up trying to be someone you aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   The low-key Isakson jokes that Gingrich's resignation sent
Georgia's conservative 6th District from ''speaker of the House to
the outhouse.'' But he knows that relative anonymity has its
rewards, notably being able to concentrate on issues important to
constituents rather than focusing on national debates, as Gingrich
did.
</P>
<P>
   So, while Gingrich's duties as speaker made committee
appearances a rarity, Isakson regularly attends meetings of the
House Transportation panel on which he serves. It's not the most
prestigious assignment, yet few policy areas are more important
around metropolitan Atlanta, where traffic concerns abound.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gingrich was an in-your-face kind of politician, whereas
Isakson is one who wants to be in your heart,'' said Jay Morgan,
who worked for both. ''I frankly think the 6th District is much
more comfortable with that kind of style even though they suffer
the indignity of having lost a speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the staunchly partisan Gingrich and the
low-key Isakson was illustrated three years ago when Georgia Gov.
Zell Miller, a Democrat who defeated Isakson in the 1990
gubernatorial race, was looking to improve the relationship between
the state's Republican schools superintendent and the
Democratic-dominated Board of Education. He tapped Isakson to chair
the board.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent a 13-month congressman can have a ''niche,''
Isakson has found one in trying to merge schools with the Internet.
House Education Chairman Bill Goodling, R-Pa., tapped him for the
Web-Based Education Commission, which examines education technology
and Internet issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pretty computer-literate for a 55-year-old,'' Isakson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before entering politics, Isakson worked for a real estate firm,
eventually becoming the company's president and a millionaire. He
honed his political skills in the Georgia House of Representatives,
where he served 14 years, half of those as the minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his failed run for governor, Isakson lost a 1996
bid for the Republican Senate nomination to businessman Guy
Millner, who then was defeated by Democrat Max Cleland.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson easily won last year's special House election,
outdistancing fellow Republican Christina Jeffrey, 65 percent to 25
percent, and faces no serious re-election challengers this fall.
</P>
<P>
   By replacing one speaker, Isakson has built a rapport with
another. Dennis Hastert of Illinois, Gingrich's successor in the
leadership post, has taken Isakson under his wing, even inviting
him on a trade mission to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Johnny Isakson and I both have the distinction of replacing
Newt Gingrich,'' Hastert said, ''but we have both learned that we
can't really replace Newt. The best we can do is use our own
talents and abilities in our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Isakson's Web site:
http://hillsource.house.gov/isakson/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 0805 </TRAILER>
