<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Agents Lose Court Fight  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today rejected a challenge
by a group of FBI agents to the bureau's limits on their
participation in the military reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, turned away the agents' argument
that they should be allowed to pursue their lawsuit in court.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 40 years, the FBI has barred agents from serving in
the military ''ready reserves,'' the reserve personnel who
participate in regular training and must be prepared for active
duty on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, agents could serve in the military ''standby reserve,''
volunteers who can be called to active duty only if insufficient
ready reservists are available. Agents who served in the standby
reserves were not allowed to volunteer for optional training
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Congress enacted the Uniformed Services Employment and
Reemployment Rights Act, which bars private and government
employers from discriminating against workers who serve in the
military reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI revised its policy in 1996 to let agents who join the
standby reserves to undergo optional training with permission from
their supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-six FBI agents who serve in the standby reserves sued,
saying the bureau's policy violated the 1994 law. A federal judge
in New York City dismissed the lawsuit, saying the agents should
have first filed an administrative complaint with the FBI's
inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals went further, ruling last
September that the law barred the agents from going into court at
all. Because of national security concerns, Congress barred
employees of federal intelligence agencies, including the FBI, from
suing over alleged violations of the law, the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, the agents' lawyers said the law
lets agents challenge the FBI's overall policy even if they cannot
go to court over decisions in individual cases.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers opposed the appeal, saying Congress wanted to
insulate intelligence agencies' personnel policies from outside
review. Agents still can go to court to argue that the FBI's policy
violates the Constitution, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Dew vs. U.S., 99-1089.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html and click on 2nd Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
