<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Who Represented Libya Loses  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former top State Department legal adviser
today lost a Supreme Court challenge of the public sanction he
received for briefly representing Libya in a lawsuit over the 1988
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 after he left his government job.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, left intact the District of Columbia
Bar's disciplinary action against Abraham Sofaer, the only lawyer
ever cited for violating ''revolving door'' rules by working in
private practice on the same matter he handled for the government.
</P>
<P>
   Sofaer denied any wrongdoing. A former federal judge and leading
figure in legal and foreign policy circles while the State
Department's top lawyer from 1985 until 1990, he once seemed a
likely Supreme Court appointee.
</P>
<P>
   Sofaer received an ''informal admonition'' -- a sanction for an
ethical violation -- in connection with criminal and civil disputes
stemming from the 1988 bombing of Pan Am Flight 103, which exploded
over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Two Libyan intelligence agents were named in U.S. indictments in
1991, and Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi refused to release them to
U.S. authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In July of 1993, Libya hired Sofaer and his law firm to
negotiate possible settlements filed by relatives of some of the
270 victims. He was to negotiate the surrender of the two accused
Libyans.
</P>
<P>
   Sofaer and the law firm dropped out of the case, amid highly
publicized criticism by victims' families, only 15 days after
signing a $3 million retainer agreement with the Libyan government.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia Court of Appeals, with final say in
lawyer-discipline matters from the nation's capital, imposed the
sanction. It said Sofaer had personally and substantially taken
part in the U.S. government's investigation of the bombing and in
related diplomatic and legal activities while with the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said Sofaer ''may have received'' information
during his government service ''that might be useful'' in
representing Libya as a private lawyer. Whether he actually
received such information was immaterial, that court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Sofaer's Supreme Court appeal said, ''The use of a broad
appearance-based standard to impose discipline is fundamentally
inconsistent with established principles of due process. A
disciplinary rule condemning improper appearance is, by definition,
a rule dependent on the eye of the beholder.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the District of Columbia urged the justices to
reject the appeal, saying. ''This is a matter of purely local
concern. ... It involves no issues of national or general
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is Sofaer vs. District of Columbia Court of Appeals,
99-1143.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
