<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massachusetts Set To Regulate Guns  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN McELHENNY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Armed with a court ruling, the state today began
enforcing the nation's first consumer protection regulation of
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a huge victory,'' said John Rosenthal of Stop Handgun
Violence, a leading proponent of gun-control measures in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules would effectively ban ''Saturday night specials,''
and require handguns sold in the state to include childproof locks,
tamper-proof serial numbers and safety warnings. Enforcement of the
rules begins immediately, the attorney general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The new gun safety regulations would not only affect
Massachusetts gun dealers, but also any gun manufacturers who want
to do business in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association this morning referred calls to
the Massachusetts-based Gun Owners Action League, which did not
immediately return a call this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Former Attorney General Scott Harshbarger wrote the rules in
1997. In an unprecedented legal maneuver, Harshbarger relied on the
attorney general's powers to regulate faulty consumer products when
he crafted the regulations that essentially banned the sale of
handguns that failed to satisfy certain safety and performance
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, Superior Court Judge Diane Kottmyer said
Harshbarger had overstepped his authority. But the Supreme Judicial
Court, the state's highest court, ruled last June that Harshbarger
had acted within his authority when he ''sought to take
preventative action as to defective handguns.''
</P>
<P>
   The court returned the case to Superior Court for further
proceedings, and in December it, too, ruled in favor of the
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The court battle ended March 20, when the gun industry failed to
meet a deadline for further appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly had been waiting to ensure the gun industry had given up
its legal battle before embarking on the full-scale enforcement
effort.
</P>
<P>
   When the high court ruled last year, Steve Ruel, a spokesman for
the Gun Owners Action League, said the high court ''made a wrong
decision because of the vagueness that is in the regulations. ... I
don't think they really understand what they've made a decision
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The state also passed a tough gun-control law in 1998 that
banned some large-capacity weapons, included penalties for gun
manufacturers who don't equip guns with proper safety locks and
owners who don't properly store their guns.
</P>
<P>
   In his December ruling, Superior Court Judge John Cratsley said
the regulations were valid except where they conflict with the 1998
law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1146 </TRAILER>
