<HEADLINE> Soybeans Rise; Grains Mixed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean prices jumped in early dealings today on
the Chicago Board of Trade, buoyed by new forecasts for mostly dry
weather in the Midwest this week. Grains were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans, which ended last week at their highest price in nearly
a year, extended the rally today on prospects that the soybean belt
will remain mostly dry. Traders said the lack of substantial
precipitation in most growing areas over the weekend helped nudge
the price higher.
</P>
<P>
   Corn opened higher on less-than-expected rain over the weekend,
then fell back.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat futures retreated after initially pushing higher on
concerns about a freeze this week in the winter wheat belt, which
accounts for most U.S. wheat production.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 2\ cents to $2.61 a bushel; May corn
was unchanged at $2.36 a bushel; July oats rose 1} cents to $1.22 a
bushel; May soybeans rose 2\ cents to $5.47} a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .07 cent to 68.87 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .25 cent to 83.65 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose .17 cent to 73.32 cents a pound; May frozen pork bellies were
unchanged at 97.20 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
