<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Sinks 247; Dow Up 119  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology shares plunged today, with Microsoft
weighing down the Nasdaq composite index. But rising financial
shares and a continuing shift to blue-chip stocks kept the Dow
Jones industrials in positive territory.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index was
down 247.12, or by 5.4 percent, at 4,325.71.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell 15 3/16 to 91 1/16 as the company appeared poised
for harsh penalties in its antitrust case. Microsoft's negotiations
with the government broke down on Saturday, and U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson was expected to rule at 5 p.m. today on
Microsoft's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Although Microsoft is also a component of the Dow, and its steep
plunge was the equivalent of more than 70 Dow points, Wall Street's
best-known indicator gained on the strength of financial stocks.
The Dow was up 119.75 at 11,041.67.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 2.98 to 1,495.60.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft wasn't the only software company suffering today.
Legato Systems, a maker of storage software, lost more than half
its value, tumbling 23 15/16 to 20 11/16. The company told the
Securities and Exchange Commission late Friday it would delay the
filing of its annual 10-K form, raising concerns that the company
would restate some financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Legato's plunge underscored investors' nervousness over the
long-term prospects of the technology shares that drove the Nasdaq
to unprecedented gains last year. Since closing at a record high
5,048.62 on March 10, the Nasdaq has fallen 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank Securities,
said the market appears to be in a ''new economy correction,'' in
which investors are driving down stocks that may have run too far
in favor of long-neglected industrial shares.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is some sense coming back into the market,'' Yardeni
said. ''Down the line, there will be a greater appreciation for
stable and predictable earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers generally define a correction as a drop of 10
percent from a peak. It signifies a reversal of an upward trend,
but doesn't necessarily mean a long-term change is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip stocks that comprise the Dow drew most buyers
today. American Express rose 6 to 154 15/16, and J.P. Morgan rose 5
5/16 to 137 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Home Depot advanced 3 to 67{.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 432.20 million
shares, well behind Friday's pace. On the Nasdaq, decliners led by
a 7-to-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 10.69 to
528.40.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas indexes were mixed. Japan's Nikkei stock average rose
2.0 percent to a new three-year high, despite the hospitalization
of the prime minister and the appointment of an acting premier. In
afternoon trading, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 1.2 percent. A
computer problem at the London Stock Exchange made it impossible to
calculate the main market index for more than four hours in early
trading.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
