<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Mergers, Acquisitions Hit Record  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. mergers and acquisitions totaled a record
2,459 during the first three months of the year as many companies
expanded overseas and technology companies continued to link up.
</P>
<P>
   The largest deal announced during the quarter was America Online
Inc.'s industry-shaking $166 billion takeover of Time Warner Inc.
In all, the announced value of mergers and acquisitions between
January and March topped $493 billion, missing the previous
quarterly high set in the second quarter of 1998 by less than $1
billion, according to Mergerstat, a Los Angeles-based company that
tracks mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the AOL-Time Warner deal, other notable takeovers
during the first part of the year included VeriSign Inc.'s $17.8
billion acquisition of Network Solutions Inc.; Ernst &AMP; Young's
$11.2 billion sale of its consulting business to France's Cap
Gemini SA; and The Tribune Co.'s $5.6 billion purchase of Times
Mirror Co.
</P>
<P>
   The investment banking firm of Goldman Sachs was the top adviser
to companies involved in mergers or acquisitions during the
quarter, followed by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell provided legal counsel in
the largest number of transactions, followed by Skadden, Arps,
Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom; and Morris, Nichols, Arsht &AMP; Tunnell.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Mergerstat: http://www.mergerstat.com
</P>
</TEXT>
