<HEADLINE> Exxon Mobil To Sell Europe Gas Unit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Exxon Mobil Corp. has agreed to sell a
gas-marketing unit, Mobil Europe Gas Inc., to Duke Energy
International.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed. The sale, announced Monday, is subject
to approval by the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Mobil Europe unit is a natural gas marketer based in the
Netherlands. The company obtains gas through contracts with Exxon
Mobil affiliates in the United Kingdom, the Netherlands and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer is a unit of Charlotte, N.C.-based Duke Energy Corp.,
the largest U.S. utility owner.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil, based in Irving, is the world's largest publicly
traded oil company. It had agreed in September to sell the unit as
part of the merger of Exxon and Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   European Union regulators approved the merger after the
companies agreed to pull out of some businesses where the
regulators had antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading Monday, Exxon Mobil shares rose 68} cents
to $78.62{, and Duke Energy Corp. shares rose 37{ cents to $52.87{
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
