<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Spending Rose in Feb.  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Construction spending grew for the fifth
straight month in February with commercial projects and
single-family homes posting big gains.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said Monday's report suggests that higher interest
rates by the Federal Reserve have yet to significantly slow
construction activity, which has been one of the main forces behind
the economy's robust growth.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on construction projects around the country jumped by a
bigger-than-expected 1.5 percent in February to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of $758.7 billion, a record level, the
Commerce Department said. Many analysts were predicting spending
would actually decline.
</P>
<P>
   ''That strength is little comfort to the Fed, which had hoped
that higher interest rates would curb construction spending and
help usher in a period of more moderate growth,'' said First Union
economist Mark Vitner.
</P>
<P>
   Construction spending in February was running about 7 percent
higher than for the same month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates five times since
June 30 to slow the speeding economy and keep inflation under
control. Given the outlook for strong continuing growth, many
economists predict the central bank will raise rates again May 16.
</P>
<P>
   In January, construction spending rose 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Economists believe that better-than-normal weather helped boost
construction spending in both January and February.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on all nonresidential, or commercial building, rose 4.8
percent to a rate of $197 billion in February. Industrial
complexes, office buildings and hotels and motels were among the
categories posting gains.
</P>
<P>
   For all residential projects, spending was up 0.6 percent to a
rate of $340.7 billion. Single-family homes led the way with a 1.3
percent increase that pushed spending to a rate of $230.7 billion.
Spending on apartment buildings, however, fell by 2.7 percent to a
rate of $28.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch economist Andrew Groat believes higher interest
rates will dampen residential activity in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on big government projects fell 0.1 percent to a rate
of $179.2 billion in February. Public housing, hospitals and
highways reported decreases in spending, while schools and military
facilities showed increases.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The construction spending report can be found:
http://www.census.gov/const/c30--curr.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1355 </TRAILER>
