<DOCNO> APW20000403.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convicted murderer wants new trial, says DA concealed evidence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) --A medical examiner tailored his trial
testimony and helped a district attorney scheme to have a man
convicted of murdering his ex-girlfriend, says the man's defense
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Rivas has been in prison since 1993 serving a 25-year to
life sentence, but allegations of prosecutorial wrongdoing may get
Rivas a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Onondaga County Judge John Brunetti has scheduled a hearing this
week to hear the issues raised by Rivas' attorney. District
Attorney William Fitzpatrick's office has denied the accusations in
its written response to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick is accused of concealing evidence and documents that
would have undermined the prosecution's theory that Rivas stalked
Valerie Hill and killed her because she had rejected his attempt to
rekindle a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's body was found in her Syracuse home on March 30, 1987.
Hill, a 28-year-old pediatrics nurse, had been strangled with the
belt of her bathrobe and sexually molested.
</P>
<P>
   Rivas, Hill's former boyfriend, was questioned at length the day
the body was found but no charges were brought. That is, until
Fitzpatrick became district attorney in 1992 and decided to reopen
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Rivas was convicted in March 1993 of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   The state Supreme Court Appellate Division upheld the conviction
in 1995. But Rivas' attorneys started further legal maneuvering's
last year after claiming they had newly discovered evidence that
warranted overturning the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The defense argues that former Medical Examiner Erik Mitchell
concluded that Hill had been dead less than 48 hours before her
body was found. Rivas, however, had an alibi for most of that time
period, and authorities opted not to charge him initially.
</P>
<P>
   The time of Hill's death and Mitchell's findings on that issue
were key factors in the 1993 trial.
</P>
<P>
   When Fitzpatrick resurrected the case and took it to trial,
Mitchell expanded the time frame for the killing by a day, a time
for which Rivas did not have an alibi.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rivas was the victim of a concerted effort to convict that was
severed from concerns over actual guilt very early on in this
investigation and was orchestrated by the district attorney
himself,'' the defense charged.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell quit his job after being charged with criminal
misconduct in the way he ran the medical examiner's office. Rivas'
attorneys said that information raises questions about Mitchell's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are suggesting that Mitchell gave false and misleading
testimony in an attempt to ingratiate himself to a district
attorney who he knew might one day be making a prosecutorial
decision regarding his gross misconduct,'' the defense claims.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the defense claims it has learned that about
potentially helpful evidence authorities had at the time but did
not provide only after requesting documents under the state's
Freedom of Information Law.
</P>
<P>
   Among that information was that police had other suspects in
Hill's slaying and that a jail inmate had told police a mentally
disabled man had confessed to the Hill slaying a year after the
crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
