<HEADLINE> Two Gang Members Convicted in N.C.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Two men were convicted Monday of
abducting and killing two young women and wounding a third woman as
part of a gang initiation.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they intend to seek the death penalty against
Eric Queen, 21, and Francisco ''Paco'' Tirado, 18, who were the
first of nine people to stand trial in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Queen and Tirado were each charged with killing Tracy Lambert,
19, and Susan Moore, 25, and wounding Debra Cheeseborough, 42, who
was shot seven times but survived.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Queen, Tirado and other members of the Crips
gang randomly picked the women as part of an initiation ritual in
1998. Prosecutors said the ''rampage of murder and mayhem'' was
carried out with bullets that had been painted blue, the Crips'
signature color.
</P>
<P>
   Tirado's lawyer said his client was not present during the
abduction or shooting of Cheeseborough. Queen's lawyers argued that
while he confessed, he should be spared because he cooperated with
investigators and had been smoking marijuana and drinking beer the
night of the crimes.
</P>
