<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Advances Made vs. Epilepsy  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- They call it ''the feeling,'' a warning some
people with epilepsy have that a seizure is imminent -- one that
they're powerless to stop.
</P>
<P>
   They can be midconversation when numbness begins stealing over
body and mind. Sometimes the seizure is a 30-second ''blank-out,''
just sitting glassy-eyed, unable to speak or move.
</P>
<P>
   Other times it's a feeling of falling, and then ... nothing. The
victim wakes in the emergency room with a horrendous headache and
no memory of convulsions.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're helpless,'' says Jeanne Carpenter of the Epilepsy
Foundation, a Washington lawyer who controls her epilepsy by taking
medication three times a day. ''You'd give anything if it would
just go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say they're finally learning enough about this
mysterious brain disorder that Carpenter's wish may, in several
more years, be within reach: Laboratory research is pointing toward
new targets for safer, better seizure-controlling therapy, even
ways to prevent some cases of epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, doctors predict patients one day might even wear
microchip-like sensors to detect the earliest stirrings of a
seizure and immediately infuse medication onto the misfiring brain
cells to quell it.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's an almost palpable excitement,'' Dr. Timothy Pedley of
New York's Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center told a conference
convened at the National Institutes of Health last week to spur the
hunt for a cure.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not going to happen all at once,'' he cautions. ''But we
are at a point in understanding brain mechanisms ... that patients
and their families are understandably saying, 'Let's talk about a
cure. Stop pussyfooting around.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some 2.3 million Americans have epilepsy, essentially periodic
electrical storms inside the brain. When the brain's electrical
circuits misfire fast enough, a seizure results. It can range from
a short glassy-eyed stare to jerking movements or the classic
convulsions and loss of consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are born with epilepsy. But up to half of the people
who suffer a brain injury -- a severe blow to the head, an infection
like meningitis, a stroke -- develop epilepsy several years later.
It's impossible to predict which ones will.
</P>
<P>
   Although two dozen drugs control seizures very well for many
patients, about 600,000 Americans aren't helped by today's
medications.
</P>
<P>
   And while surgery can cure some types of epilepsy, such as
''temporal lobe epilepsy,'' far too few of the tens of thousands of
ideal candidates ever get the operation, said Dr. Marc Dichter of
the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Brain surgery sounds scary, explained Dr. Martha Morrell of
Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   Headlines are made by the incredibly rare, radical operations in
which a child with severe, unrelenting seizures has half a brain
removed. That's not the surgery most epilepsy patients need,
Morrell stressed. Most candidates have misfiring neurons in just
one small spot that sophisticated brain scans can pinpoint,
allowing ''very conservative and very safe'' surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The future of epilepsy care is poised to come from recent,
exciting molecular discoveries about just which brain chemicals,
cells and genes react in different ways to cause seizures.
Scientists issued a call last week to hurry up and turn those
discoveries into treatments doctors can test.
</P>
<P>
   For example, scientists now know that loss of a protein called
cystatin B causes increasingly bad seizures in ''progressive
myoclonus epilepsy.'' A logical next step is to give back patients
that missing protein, maybe as a drug. ''What are we waiting for?''
asked Dr. Jeffrey Noebels of Houston's Baylor College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are pinpointing the neurochemicals that spark
abnormal electrical signals and formation of some abnormal brain
circuits and finding a slew of novel drug targets.
</P>
<P>
   Another huge quest is to create neuroprotective drugs to keep
people from developing epilepsy after a brain injury.
</P>
<P>
   Still other scientists are trying to create those microchip-like
sensors to detect seizures early, and tiny implantable pumps that
could infuse anti-seizure medicine just on the misfiring cells
instead of medicating the whole brain.
</P>
<P>
   Sensors and drug pumps are more than a decade away, but
scientists say clinical trials of some other novel treatments could
start in as little as a year.
</P>
<P>
   Patients can help in the quest: Scientists are hunting families
with a history of epilepsy to hunt related genes.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're a patient who isn't seizure-free, Morrell advises
seeking care at an epilepsy specialty center. General physicians
won't understand as well as specialists the differences between the
24 medications or who is a good surgery candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The Epilepsy Foundation can provide information on gene studies
and epilepsy care at http://www.efa.org.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical
issues for The Associated Press in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1411 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
