<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wheelchair Mom Has Case Dismissed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDUSKY, Ohio (AP) -- An appeals court has overturned the
conviction of a woman with muscular dystrophy who rode her
wheelchair in a street.
</P>
<P>
   The 6th Ohio District Court of Appeals in Toledo said Kelly
Dillery did not receive a speedy trial on the charge of being a
pedestrian in the street, a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   A Municipal Court judge in Sandusky had found Dillery guilty and
fined her $100. But the appeals court ruled Friday that she had the
right to go to trial 30 days after she was served with a summons on
Dec. 4, 1998. Her trial began Jan. 21, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal means she can't be tried again in the case. She
still faces the same charge in another case, but prosecutors were
unsure if they would try her, since she has moved to Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Dillery, 31, has repeatedly insisted that she be allowed to ride
in streets when she can't get her wheelchair onto sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, she was acquitted of a child-endangering charge that
arose after she allegedly rode her wheelchair in a street with her
4-year-old daughter strapped to her lap.
</P>
<P>
   Dillery is suing Sandusky, alleging the city violated her civil
rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
