<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Toughens Asylum Rules  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The government's introduction Monday of tough new
measures to deter asylum seekers came under immediate criticism
from a leading British charity, which said it would refuse to
accept the vouchers given to the refugees instead of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new initiative, asylum seekers no longer will be given
cash grants. Instead, they will get vouchers, which can then be
exchanged at participating stores for food and other necessities.
However, any change will go to the store instead of back to the
refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Oxfam, a major charity that runs a network of shops selling used
clothes and other goods, condemned the measure as
''penny-pinching'' and said it would not accept the vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Refugee Council chief executive Nick Hardwick said the new
system would ''stigmatize and demean asylum-seekers and make one of
society's most vulnerable groups even more exposed to potential
hostility.''
</P>
<P>
   Other new measures include imposing fines of $3,180 on truckers
who smuggle in illegal immigrants, and the forced dispersal of
asylum-seekers around the country to take pressure off London and
southeast England, where many refugees are now concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   ''If people are genuinely fleeing from countries like Iraq, then
they won't mind at all going to a perfectly civilized city like
Glasgow,'' Home Secretary Jack Straw said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
   The measures are the latest attempt by Prime Minister Tony
Blair's Labor Party government to curb the soaring number of
asylum-seekers. The government says most are simply seeking a
better way of life, sometimes attracted by reports of generous
welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Home Office says the number of asylum-seekers shot to
a record 71,160 last year, mostly coming from the former Yugoslavia
and Sri Lanka. The influx represented a 50 percent increase from
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new measures, asylum-seekers will get $16 cash a week,
and vouchers worth between $30 and $42 depending on the recipient's
age.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Conservative Party complained that the Labor
government wasn't going far enough to try to curb the number of
refugees entering Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Tory spokeswoman Ann Widdecombe said, if in power, the
Conservatives would make greater use of detention as a deterrent to
unjustified asylum claims.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will send out one very simple message,'' she told the
British Broadcasting Corp. ''If you come to Britain with an
unfounded claim, one, you will be detained; two, you will be dealt
with quickly; and three, you will be removed.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1455 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
