<DOCNO> APW20000403.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Educators Fall Short on World Goal  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Failing to meet a decade-old goal of assuring
every child on earth an education by this year, world educators,
human rights groups and politicians are giving themselves 15 more
years.
</P>
<P>
   With 125 million children still out of school, the challenge is
huge and the cost up to $8 billion a year. But the Global Campaign
for Education, launched in five far-flung cities Monday, has new
tools and new supporters: the Internet and teachers unions around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   With announcements in Washington, New Delhi, India, Durban,
South Africa, Sao Paulo, Brazil, and Brussels, Belgium, teachers
groups and non-government organizations operating in 180 countries
started a campaign to pressure governments and global financial
institutions into achieving universal education.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 governments have committed to the 2015 goal after
it became clear they couldn't meet the 10-year goal first set at an
international education conference in 1990. The next U.N.-sponsored
global forum is set for Dakar, Senegal, April 26-28.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot afford to sit by while one in three people in the
developing world is growing up illiterate,'' said Bob Chase,
president of the National Education Association, at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The rival American Federation of Teachers also has joined the
campaign, along with teachers' and other child advocacy groups
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a basic human right that must be met. No child anywhere
on earth should be denied an education,'' said Sandra Feldman, AFT
president, in a statement released at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The effort includes e-mail and postcard campaigns calling for
increased aid, debt relief, more private investment in education
and more help for African countries specifically. Organizers cite
successes in Uganda, where enrollment went from 50 percent to 90
percent in two years, and Malawi, where a campaign doubled
enrollment of girls in primary education.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, President Clinton's National Economic Council
director, endorsed the campaign, citing the administration's
efforts to gain debt relief for poorer countries which are unable
to educate all their children and moves to halt child labor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The opportunity for universal education is there,'' said
Sperling. ''This is as important as any cause that any of us can
work on.'' He added that dollars spent on education abroad go
farther both economically and morally than other foreign
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Oxfam International, a non-government development agency, and
the Global March Against Child Labor are among groups leading a
week-long global effort to get governments to commit more resources
to education.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe citizens around the world can come together and
make a difference,'' said Raymond C. Offenheiser, Oxfam president.
</P>
<P>
   Pharis Harvey, an organizer of the global campaign against child
labor, said for the United States to be a leader in the effort it
must do more to meet the needs of its own child laborers,
especially the hundreds of thousands of migrant farm worker
children.
</P>
<P>
   He said 45 percent of migrant children drop out of school
without the skills to compete for the lowest paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the richest nation on earth cannot adequately include these
children, we cannot call on other nations with fewer resources or
less commitment to solve their inadequacies,'' Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.campaignforeducation.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1456 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000403.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Wanted UN War Crimes Suspects  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   RADOVAN KARADZIC: Former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic
has been indicted by the U.N. war crimes tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia for crimes against humanity and violating the customs of
war during the Bosnian conflict.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1995, he was also charged with genocide for masterminding the
slaughter of more than 6,000 Muslims in the U.N.-protected
Srebrenica enclave in northeastern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1992-95 war, Karadzic served as the first Bosnian
Serb president. He was replaced by his deputy, Biljana Plavsic, in
1996 and was last seen in public that September.
</P>
<P>
   He fled his stronghold village of Pale, east of Sarajevo, and is
believed to be hiding somewhere in Bosnia, in the French-controlled
southeastern zone.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-led peacekeepers in Bosnia have been reluctant to go after
him, because he is reportedly heavily protected by armed personal
security guards. Belgrade sources close to Karadzic say he has lost
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war, Karadzic was a psychiatrist in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   If arrested, he could implicate Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, who is widely blamed for instigating the Croatian and
Bosnian wars.
</P>
<P>
   RATKO MLADIC: Former Bosnian Serb military commander Ratko
Mladic has also been indicted by the U.N. tribunal for crimes
against humanity, violating the customs of war and genocide during
the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 he led Yugoslav troops in Knin, Croatia and one year
later, assumed command of the forces of the Yugoslav army's 2nd
military district, which effectively became the Bosnian Serb army.
</P>
<P>
   Mladic led the Bosnian Serb military for the duration of the
war, under Karadzic, with whom he shares an indictment for genocide
linked to the massacre at Srebrenica.
</P>
<P>
   He was ousted from his post in December 1996, and remains at
large. Mladic has frequently been seen in Serbia, most recently
last Tuesday, when he showed up -- flanked by eight bodyguards -- at
a soccer match between Yugoslavia and China.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely believed that Mladic lives in Belgrade's Dedinje
district, where Milosevic also has his home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1459 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000403.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People Back Campaign Finance Change  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two-thirds of Americans in a survey say they
support campaign finance reform, including public financing of
elections, according to a group that backs the overhaul of laws on
campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   Public polls on the topic consistently have shown support for
overhauling campaign finance laws, but they also place campaign
finance reform near the bottom as a priority issue.
</P>
<P>
   Only a third of the people in the survey conducted by Democratic
pollster Mark Mellman for Public Campaign ranked the influence of
special-interest money as a top concern.
</P>
<P>
   Three-fourths of those in the poll said George W. Bush's raising
of more than $70 million was more a symptom of what is wrong with
fund raising than a sign of broad-based support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 800 likely voters conducted March 20-23 had an error
margin of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Nyhart, executive director of the nonpartisan Public
Campaign, noted that four states -- Arizona, Massachusetts, Maine
and Vermont -- have adopted full public financing of campaigns for
candidates who agree to not take private donations and to limit
spending.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of the candidates' proposals for campaign finance
reform, Nyhart said Bush's ''dances around the edges'' while the
plan of likely Democratic nominee Al Gore ''is very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Gore is an appropriate messenger for widespread
campaign finance reform -- Gore said he was an ''imperfect
messenger'' because of allegations about his past fund raising --
Nyhart said that any candidate who gets to be the likely nominee of
a major party ''has had to raise money from special interests to
get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
