<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bodies Causing Disease in Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VLADIKAVKAZ, Russia (AP) -- Bodies of people killed in the
Chechen war are decomposing in a river and causing scores of
villagers to come down with typhoid fever, local officials said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The report of 74 cases of the potentially fatal disease in the
village of Lermontov-Yurt came during a lull in the war that has
gripped the republic for seven months. It adds a new dimension to
the plight of Chechnya's people, most of whom have lost homes and
family members in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The war has left hundreds of unburied bodies, many lying in the
republic's forests and mountains or at the bottom of its waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Some 300 bodies of rebels still lie in a minefield outside the
Chechen capital Grozny, where they died while trying to flee the
capital in early February, said the Kremlin's spokesman on
Chechnya, Sergei Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a water-supply system, or even a well in some
villages, most Chechens use river water for drinking. And a lack of
firewood often means the water is not boiled.
</P>
<P>
   In Lermontov-Yurt, 19 of the 74 people diagnosed with typhoid
fever have been hospitalized, said local officials, who blamed the
outbreak on water from a nearby river contaminated by dead bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Galina Lazikova, a senior official at the epidemic control
department of Russia's Health Ministry, warned Monday that similar
outbreaks could be expected throughout the republic.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is no guaranteed water supply, anything can be
expected,'' Lazikova said on the Echo of Moscow radio station.
''People are drinking nobody-knows-what kind of water, contaminated
with nobody-knows-what.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We can expect outbreaks of any intestinal disease ... even
cholera,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No large battles were reported in Chechnya over the past day,
Yastrzhembsky told a news conference Monday. But Chechen rebels
continue to descend from the mountains and stage surprise attacks
in the Russian-controlled lowlands, said Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops have driven the main rebel forces out of the
northern flatlands into the mountains that make up Chechnya's
southern third, but seem unable to progress much further.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian troops continued combing the Vedeno district
deep in the southern mountains, in a search for at least 11
comrades missing after a rebel ambush last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At least 43 Russian servicemen died as a result of the ambush --
the latest in a series of attacks that inflicted heavy losses on
the Russians and showed their vulnerability to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The economic toll the war is taking on Russia's strained budget
has never been disclosed. But First Deputy Prime Minister Mikhail
Kasyanov said Moscow spent $210 million on the offensive in the
first quarter of this year, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sent ground troops into Chechnya in September, following
weeks of air strikes, after Chechnya-based rebels invaded the
neighboring republic of Dagestan. The rebels are also blamed for
apartment bombings in Russia in September that killed some 300
people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
