<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burglars Kill German Family in China  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Burglars killed a German auto executive and his
family in their home in the eastern Chinese city of Nanjing,
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The DaimlerChrysler executive, who had lived in China since
1997, his wife, son and daughter were stabbed Saturday night, a
German Foreign Ministry spokesman said in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Pfrang was the deputy general manager of Yaxing-Benz, a
joint venture in Jiangsu province, where Nanjing is the capital.
Mercedes-Benz is a unit of DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler would not release the names of Pfrang's wife and
children, aged 11 and 14. The foreign ministry spokesman would only
say that the family was from the southern state of
Baden-Wuerttemburg.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was unusual for China, where crimes against
foreigners are rare and the rate of reported crime is relatively
low. The German Foreign Ministry said there was no record of such a
crime ever being committed in China before.
</P>
<P>
   The burglars -- four young farmers -- killed Pfrang, 50, and his
family after he confronted them, said a German diplomat in China.
Police called in by security guards arrested the burglars in the
residential compound where the family house was located.
</P>
<P>
   The official Xinhua News Agency said the burglars had confessed,
and the agency stressed that police believed the break-in had no
political overtones.
</P>
<P>
   ''The attack was random, and did not specially target
foreigners,'' Xinhua said. The German Foreign Ministy concurred.
</P>
<P>
   The burglars had first ransacked an unoccupied house before
breaking into the Pfrang home, the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   A DaimlerChrysler spokeswoman said the company was shocked by
the killings and praised the quick Chinese police work in arresting
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Yaxing-Benz has 38 German employees in Yangzhou, a city near
Nanjing where it makes buses, the spokeswoman said by telephone
from Stuttgart, Germany. About 60 Germans total live in the region,
the German Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
