<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Monday, April 3, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Ruling To Come Late Today
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal judge overseeing the Microsoft
antitrust trial prepared to release his verdict today after the
close of trading on Wall Street. The ruling follows the collapse of
negotiations between Microsoft and the government. A recording for
the federal courthouse said U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson would disclose his ''findings of law'' today after
financial markets closed. Stock in Microsoft Corp. lost 13 percent
of its value today after the news was disclosed. The judge was
expected to rule against Microsoft, based on harsh assessments he
outlined last November in his ''findings of fact.'' In that
document, Jackson found that Microsoft repeatedly engaged in
anti-competitive behavior by taking advantage of its monopoly
power. The charges were made in a lawsuit filed against the company
by the government and 19 states.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Sinks 245; Dow Up 229
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology shares plunged today, with Microsoft
weighing down the Nasdaq composite index. But rising financial
shares and a continuing shift to blue-chip stocks helped the Dow
Jones industrials soar. Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Nasdaq
composite index was down 245.80 at 4,327.03. Microsoft fell 14 9/16
to 91 11/16 as the company appeared poised for harsh penalties in
its antitrust case. Microsoft's negotiations with the government
broke down on Saturday, and U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson was expected to rule at 5 p.m. EDT today on Microsoft's
guilt. Although Microsoft is also a component of the Dow, and its
steep plunge was the equivalent of more than 70 Dow points, Wall
Street's best-known indicator gained on the strength of financial
stocks. The Dow was up 229.81 at 11,151.73.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EDT:
