</P>
<P>
   Education Institutions Unite on Net
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Six of the world's top educational institutions,
including Columbia University and the London School of Economics
and Political Science, said today they are forming ''the premier
site for knowledge and education on the Internet.'' The new site,
called Fathom, is expected to debut this summer and also will
include contributions from the Cambridge University Press, the
British Library, the New York Public Library and the Smithsonian
Institution's National Museum of Natural History. The for-profit
Internet site will have many free offerings, but other information
will be provided for a fee. Advertising is also expected to be a
component of the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Construction Spending Rose in Feb.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Spending on construction projects around the
country rose 1.5 percent in February, led by a big jump in
commercial building. The Commerce Department reported today that
construction spending climbed to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of $758.7 billion, an all-time high monthly level. February's
performance was stronger than many analysts were predicting. In
January, construction spending grew by 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing Economy Keeps Growing
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. manufacturing economy continued to grow
in March, but at a slower rate than in February. And there were
warnings that prices for energy and raw materials were rising. Of
20 industries surveyed by the National Association of Purchasing
Management, 17 reported higher prices. The index of the
manufacturing economy was at 55.8 percent in March, down from 56.9
February, but well above the reading of 50 that indicates growth.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil To Sell Europe Gas Unit
</P>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Exxon Mobil Corp. has agreed to sell a
gas-marketing unit, Mobil Europe Gas Inc., to Duke Energy
International. Terms were not disclosed for the sale announced
today, which is subject to approval by the European Commission. The
Mobil Europe unit is a natural gas marketer based in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel To Sell Software Unit
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mattel Inc. is putting its troubled Learning
Company division up for sale, less than a year after the giant
toymaker bought the software business to help step up its high-tech
offerings. The world's largest toymaker said today that it has
retained investment firm Credit Suisse First Boston Corp. to sell
the money-losing Learning Company, which has been a burden to
Mattel since it was acquired last May for $3.6 billion. Problems
with the Learning Company led to Jill E. Barad's resignation in
February as Mattel's chairman and chief executive officer. She
announced her departure after Mattel reported a steep
fourth-quarter and year-end loss, mostly due to troubles with the
software business.
</P>
<P>
   US Mergers, Acquisitions Hit Record
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. mergers and acquisitions totaled a record
2,459 during the first three months of the year as many companies
expanded overseas and technology companies continued to link up.
The largest deal announced during the quarter was America Online
Inc.'s industry-shaking $166 billion takeover of Time Warner Inc.
In all, the announced value of mergers and acquisitions between
January and March topped $493 billion, missing the previous
quarterly high set in the second quarter of 1998 by less than $1
billion, according to Mergerstat, a Los Angeles-based company that
tracks mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS Drug Given to S. Africa's Poor
</P>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. is offering to
give away an expensive AIDS drug to poor South Africans, a move
that follows a series of protests and raises hopes other
pharmaceutical companies will follow suit. The drug, Diflucan,
treats cryptococcal meningitis, a lethal brain infection that
occurs in nearly one out of 10 HIV-patients. In South Africa, the
daily dose of Diflucan costs about $15, far more than the country's
many poor can afford. Those with the infection must take medication
for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today Unveils New Design
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- USA Today, whose innovative design helped
change the face of America's newspapers, unveiled an updated look
today. The Gannett Co. paper, headquartered in Arlington and
printed at 36 sites around the world, is being changed to a page
1.25 inches narrower and one-half inch taller. Readers will find
the new paper easier to handle in small spaces such as airplane
seats, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora Names CEO, Restates Earnings
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Aurora Foods Inc., owner of such well-known
brands as Duncan Hines and Aunt Jemima, named a new chief executive
today and restated its earnings for 1998 and 1999 based on an
investigation into its accounting practices. Aurora said James T.
Smith, a former executive at food company ConAgra, would be its CEO
and president. It also named Christopher T. Sortwell, a former
executive with the brewer The Stroh Cos., as executive vice
president and chief financial officer. In February, four executives
including the CEO and CFO at Aurora resigned as the company
announced the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer Purchases Polyols Business
</P>
<P>
   LEVERKUSEN, Germany (AP) -- Chemical giant Bayer Corp. has
completed the purchase of the polyols business of Lyondell Chemical
Co. for $2.45 billion in a deal that makes the German company the
world's largest producer of polyurethane raw material. With the
purchase, Bayer's polyurethane division will increase to an
estimated $2.9 billion from $2.1 billion in 1999, the company said
today. The deal had been announced in November. Polyurethane has a
multitude of uses, including for production of safety dashboards in
vehicles, electronics production, as well as for insulation and
soft synthetic sponge for mattresses.
</P>
<P>
   Rexam Buying American National Can
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Britain's Rexam PLC has agreed to buy American
National Can, the world's second-largest producer of aluminum
beverage cans, for $2.1 billion. The deal announced today completes
Rexam's three-year plan to reshape the London-based manufacturer of
cans, cartons and boxes around consumer packaging activities and
gives it a strong entry into the North American can market, said
Rolf Brjesson, Rexam chief executive. Rexam is paying $18 a share,
well above Friday's closing price of $13.12{ a share for American
National Can.
</P>
