<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Sinks 301; Dow Up 230  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft devastated the Nasdaq composite index
today, falling steeply in advance of a judge's ruling in its
antitrust case. But rising financial shares and a continuing shift
to blue-chip stocks helped the Dow Jones industrials soar.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite index was down 301.76, or by 6.5 percent, at
4,271.07. The index was on track for its worst performance in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell 15\ to 91 as the company appeared poised for
harsh penalties, including a possible order to break itself up.
Microsoft's negotiations with the government broke down on
Saturday, and U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson was
expected to rule at 5 p.m. today on Microsoft's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Although Microsoft is also a component of the Dow, and its steep
plunge was the equivalent of more than 75 Dow points, Wall Street's
best-known indicator gained on the strength of financial stocks.
The Dow was up 230.82 at 11,152.74.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 2.66 to 1,501.24, and the
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 13.89 to 525.20.
</P>
<P>
   Other high-tech decliners included Legato Systems, a maker of
storage software, which lost more than half its value, tumbling 24
13/16 to 19 13/16. The company told the Securities and Exchange
Commission late Friday it would delay the filing of its annual 10-K
form, raising concerns that the company would restate some
financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Legato's plunge underscored investors' nervousness over the
long-term prospects of the technology shares that drove the Nasdaq
to unprecedented gains last year. Since closing at a record high
5,048.62 on March 10, the Nasdaq has fallen 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank Securities,
said the market appears to be in a ''new economy correction,'' in
which investors are driving down stocks that may have run too far
in favor of long-neglected industrial shares.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is some sense coming back into the market,'' Yardeni
said. ''Down the line, there will be a greater appreciation for
stable and predictable earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers generally define a correction as a drop of 10
percent from a peak. It signifies a reversal of an upward trend,
but doesn't necessarily mean a long-term change is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip stocks that comprise the Dow drew most buyers
today. American Express rose 8[ to 157 1/16, and J.P. Morgan rose
6\ to 138.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Home Depot advanced 3[ to 67|.
</P>
<P>
   Investors weren't completely shunning technology stocks. Shares
of companies that make Linux software rose on the prospect that any
court-ordered breakup of Microsoft could stimulate demand for
Linux-based operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat rose 1 7/16 to 43 13/16 and VA Linux rose 3 5/16 to 63
11/16 on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   With Microsoft occupying center stage on Wall Street and in
Washington, investors paid little attention to the latest report
from the National Association of Purchasing Management. The group
reported that growth in the manufacturing economy continued in
March, but at slower rate than February.
</P>
<P>
   The purchasing managers also warned about the rising cost of
energy and raw materials.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing issues narrowly
outnumbered decliners. Volume came to 776.26 million shares, well
behind Friday's pace. On the Nasdaq, decliners led by a 3-to-1
margin.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas indexes were mixed. Japan's Nikkei stock average rose
2.0 percent to a new three-year high, despite the hospitalization
of the prime minister and the appointment of an acting premier.
Britain's FT-SE 100 closed down 1.2 percent. A computer problem at
the London Stock Exchange made it impossible to calculate the main
market index for more than four hours in early trading.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
