<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Canker Quarantine Expanded  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Stepping up their battle against citrus
canker, Florida agriculture officials expanded the quarantine zones
Monday and ordered that all field hands statewide disinfect
themselves and their equipment before entering or leaving citrus
groves.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus canker poses a major threat to Florida's $8.5 billion
citrus industry. The plant disease causes fruit to fall prematurely
and ultimately can kill the tree.
</P>
<P>
   To date, more than 200,000 residential trees and more than
300,000 commercial trees have been destroyed in a $174 million
eradication effort.
</P>
<P>
   The 773-square-mile Miami-Dade and Broward County quarantine
area was expanded to nearly 1,000 square miles, north to the Palm
Beach County line and south to Florida Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Collier County's quarantine area expanded westward from 43
square miles to 77 square miles. Hendry County has a new quarantine
area of 16 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to stay ahead of the spread of canker, and expanding
these quarantine areas will help us do that,'' said Agriculture
Commissioner Bob Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the quarantine areas may not move citrus trees,
fruit, leaves or stems from their property. They also may not
exchange citrus fruit with anyone or plant new citrus trees. They
are required to dispose of any citrus fruit or debris in doubled
plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   The new decontamination measure requires that all workers wash
themselves and clean their equipment before entering and leaving
property containing citrus plants, even if the grove is not
infected.
</P>
<P>
   Workers can decontaminate themselves with antibacterial soap and
clean their equipment with an ammonia solution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1543 </TRAILER>
