<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mixed; Wheat Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures tumbled Monday on the Chicago Board
of Trade, while other grains and soybeans finished mixed.
</P>
<P>
   An early-session rally carrying over from Friday, driven by
concerns about a crop-harming freeze this week in the winter wheat
belt, failed to hold in the wheat futures market. Prices sank
nearly 2 percent for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Investors appeared to have second thoughts about the chances of
crop damage from cold weather in wheat-growing regions over the
next two nights. The decline also was fueled by the slump in corn.
</P>
<P>
   Corn prices also got early support from dry weather concerns
before retreating. Fears that foot-and-mouth disease in South Korea
could spread added to the selling mood.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans rose slightly despite pressure from wheat and corn.
After ending last week at their highest price in nearly a year,
soybeans extended the rally on prospects that the soybean belt will
remain mostly dry. The lack of substantial precipitation in most
growing areas over the weekend helped nudge the price higher.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 4{ cents to $2.57} a bushel; May
corn fell 1} cent to $2.34\ a bushel; July oats rose 2 cents to
$1.21 a bushel; May soybeans rose 1 cent to $5.46{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
while pork futures were higher.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .18 cent to 69.15 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .02 cent to 83.90 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose .12 cent to 73.27 cents a pound; May pork bellies rose .05
cent to 97.35 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
