<HEADLINE> Poll: Gore Leads Bush in N.Y.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Al Gore had a double-digit lead over George
W. Bush in a New York poll out Monday, while Bush had the advantage
over Gore in a survey taken in traditionally Republican Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The two were tied in a new poll that came out in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The New York poll from Marist College's Institute for Public
Opinion showed the vice president ahead of the Texas governor, 49
percent to 38 percent. Gore has led Bush in several New York polls
out this winter, though the two were close in Marist polls last
December and earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates are in a statistical dead heat among male
voters, with 46 percent supporting Gore and 42 percent for Bush,
but Gore leads Bush among women, 53 percent to 35 percent. The
telephone poll of 561 registered voters was conducted March 27-28
and has an error margin of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore were tied at 46 percent apiece in a Wisconsin poll
taken by St. Norbert College from March 1-23 of 574 likely voters
with an error margin of plus or minus 4 percentage points. Bush led
Gore by 54 percent to 36 percent in an Indiana poll of 651
registered voters taken March 26-29 by the University of Indiana
Center for Survey Research with an error margin of plus or minus
4.5 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
