<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Livestock Disease Strikes S. Korea  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A provincial government in South Korea
indefinitely closed all livestock markets Monday amid increasing
fears that the deadly foot-and-mouth disease could become a
national epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Kyonggi province, which surrounds but does not include the
capital Seoul, said it will close all 32 livestock markets to
prevent further spread of the fatal ailment. Other provinces and
cities are expected to follow suit, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Since symptoms of foot-and-mouth disease began showing up around
March 20 at two farms in Paju in Kyonggi province, north of Seoul,
several more farms farther south are believed to have been
infected, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem requires an all-out government effort to be
controlled. It threatens to become a national epidemic,''
Agriculture Minister Kim Sung-hoon told a Cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The government confirmed Sunday that the disease in Paju was
foot-and-mouth. It was the first confirmed outbreak of the disease
in Asia since it wiped out nearly all of Taiwan's pigs three years
ago. Seoul has not confirmed whether the illness in other areas was
the same disease.
</P>
<P>
   Foot-and-mouth disease is highly communicable and can kill
carrier animals and ruin entire beef and milk-cow herds. It cannot
be passed on to people.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has also reported suspected outbreaks of the disease in 19
cows on two farms since Saturday, and officials are testing
thousands more.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Japan and South Korea to suspend imports of beef
and pork from each other. Australia, Taiwan, Hong Kong and
Singapore also banned imports from both countries. China prepared
to join them.
</P>
<P>
   In North Korea, which suffers from chronic food shortages, the
government has not confirmed any cases. But South Korean
intelligence officials said the ailment may have cropped up there.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Hongsong, a major cattle growing area 60 miles
south of Seoul, became the second region to be hit by the suspected
disease. So far, hundreds of cattle and pigs have been slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Yongi and Hwasong, two more villages along the
western coast about 50 miles away from Hongsong, reported that
their cattle and pigs had blisters in their mouths, typical
symptoms of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities sealed off the areas and began inoculating hundreds
of thousands of animals. Officials slaughtered infected livestock,
burned barns and banned imports of Chinese hay suspected of having
transmitted the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers set up roadblocks and let vehicles and travelers pass
only after being thoroughly fumigated or sanitized. But officials
fear the highly contagious disease might already have spread.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak of the disease is threatening South Korea's farm
industry. South Korea last year exported 89,000 tons of pork to
Japan. It exports little beef.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1607 </TRAILER>
