<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down iggest Fall; Dow Up 300  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology shares plunged Monday, with a
tumbling Microsoft dragging down the Nasdaq composite index to its
biggest point drop ever. But rising shares in financial businesses
pushed the Dow industrials sharply higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index plummeted 348.58 points, or by 7.7
percent, to close at 4,224.25, according to preliminary figures.
That was far beyond the previous record daily drop of 229.46
points, set Jan. 4, and also was the fifth-biggest daily percentage
decline.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-focused index had plunged 390.20 points last
week, even with a rally Friday. Since closing at a record high
5,048.62 on March 10, the Nasdaq now has fallen more than 16
percent. But even with the decline, the Nasdaq is 3.8 percent above
where it began the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average shot up 300.01 points, or 2.7
percent, to close at 11,221.93, according to preliminary
calculations. Last week, the Dow fell 190.80. Even with Monday's
increase, it was off about 4.3 percent from its Jan. 14 record of
11,722.98 and 2.4 percent below where it began the year.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell $15.56\ to $90.68} a share in late trading as the
company appeared poised for harsh penalties in the government's
antitrust case. Negotiations broke down Saturday, and U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson was expected to issue a verdict after
markets closed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank Securities,
said the market appeared to be in a ''new economy correction,'' in
which investors were driving down stocks that may have run too far
in favor of long-neglected industrial shares.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is some sense coming back into the market,'' Yardeni
said. ''Down the line, there will be a greater appreciation for
stable and predictable earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers generally define a correction as a drop of 10
percent from a peak. It signifies a reversal of an upward trend but
doesn't necessarily mean a long-term change is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Microsoft is a component of the Dow, Wall Street's
best-known indicator gained, because of the strength of financial
stocks. American Express and J.P. Morgan both were up sharply.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing issues narrowly
outnumbered decliners. Volume came to 776.26 million shares in late
trading, well behind Friday's pace. On the Nasdaq, decliners led by
a 3-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.0 percent to a
three-year high, despite the hospitalization of the prime minister
and the appointment of an acting premier.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
