<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court allows lawsuit from man hit by patrol car  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A state appeals court has pierced the wall
of immunity that protects police officers from being sued by people
who are injured as a result of high-speed chases.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled Monday that Martin Torres of Perth Amboy has the
right to sue the city police department and the officer who struck
him while chasing a van that had violated the speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, there have been spectacular -- and sometimes
fatal -- crashes arising from high-speed police chases, and in most
of them the courts have ruled that injury lawsuits cannot be filed.
</P>
<P>
   State laws protect police from a flurry of such lawsuits,
sticking to the legal doctrine that to expose police to such
liability would intimidate them from doing their jobs aggressively.
This legal safety net is broken only when it can be shown that a
police officer acted recklessly or with extreme negligence to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   But appeals court Judge William D'Annunzio, writing for a
unanimous three-judge panel, said Monday this so-called ''hot
pursuit'' legal standard applies only when there is a real police
chase going on, and they define this as a situation in which a
criminal suspect knows the police are after him and he decides to
evade capture.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the court said the immunity from lawsuits does
not apply to speeding-ticket cases because the person who is being
pursued does not know it and is making no effort to evade capture.
</P>
<P>
   The Perth Amboy patrolman spotted a van exceeding the speed
limit by more than 20 mph, so he said he made a U-turn, activated
his lights and increased the speed of the patrol car to catch up
with the van and pull it over.
</P>
<P>
   Torres crossed the street at an intersection and was struck by
the patrol car. He suffered two broken bones in his spine and
multiple fractures to his leg. Torres claimed the light was green
for him to cross and that the officer had activated neither his car
lights, nor his siren. The officer claimed Torres was crossing at a
red light, and that the patrol car's lights and siren were on.
</P>
<P>
   A trial judge dismissed Torres' lawsuit on the grounds the
police officer and the city were protected by immunity.
</P>
<P>
   These disputes about whether the lights and siren were on were
not relevant to the appeals court because they concerned themselves
with the dismissal of the case. Issues of what actually occurred
will be up to a jury to decide.
</P>
<P>
   The basis of Judge D'Annunzio's ruling was that this was not a
''pursuit'' under legal definitions because the alleged speeder
driving the van was not trying to evade the police and in fact
probably did not know he was being chased.
</P>
<P>
   ''The crucial element of this definition is the officer's
reasonable belief that the pursued vehicle is aware of a police
attempt to stop the vehicle and the pursued driver is resisting
apprehension by increasing vehicle speed, ignoring the officer or
otherwise attempting to elude the officer,'' D'Annunzio wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''A pursuit creates an enhanced risk of mishap and injury,'' the
judge wrote. ''In contrast, a police officer's attempt to close the
gap on a speeding vehicle that is not attempting to flee does not
involve the risk (factors) of a pursuit.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Annunzio said immunity from liability in real police chases is
essential ''to promote police participation in the high-risk action
without the inhibiting concern of a civil reprisal. Such a
rationale is less important in the context of lower-risk events
such as (the officer's) attempt to close the gap and stop a
nonfleeing speeder.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for the city, Frederick Rubenstein, would not
comment, referring calls to city police officials, who were not
immediately available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-03-00 1629 </TRAILER>
