<HEADLINE> Maine Outlaws Use of 'Squaw'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) -- All Maine communities and natural
landmarks containing the word ''squaw'' -- a term considered
offensive to women and Indians -- will be renamed under a bill
signed Monday by Gov. Angus King.
</P>
<P>
   A special commission will recommend new names, which are
expected to take effect next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just an issue of being politically correct,'' said
Tony Sprague, a spokesman for the governor. ''This is a term that
is offensive to them and it shouldn't be used in public places.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ''squaw'' roughly translates to ''whore.''
</P>
<P>
   The law affects about two dozen mountains, waterways and other
features, such as Squaw Pond and Big and Little Squaw townships.
Private entities aren't affected.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Penobscot, Pasamaquoddy, Micmac and Maliseet
tribes were present as the bill was signed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It took a lot of work from people in the native communities to
open up and talk about something that's as heartfelt as this,''
said Rep. Donald Soctomah, the Passamaquoddy Tribe's representative
and sponsor of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota and Montana have adopted similar laws, and in
Colorado, even the endangered squawfish was renamed the Colorado
pikeminnow.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Donna Loring, the Penobscot Nation's representative, said
the bill's approval showed that tribal-state relations are
improving.
</P>
<P>
   The law will affect map-making nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a huge deal for us,'' said Charles Conley, marketing
manager for Freeport map company DeLorme Inc. ''Part of being a
mapmaker is knowing you'll always be making revisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
