<HEADLINE> Emergency Appeal by White House  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an emergency appeal, the Clinton
administration asked a federal appeals court Monday to set aside a
judge's finding that President Clinton committed a crime when he
released letters from presidential accuser Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday's ruling by U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth, a
Reagan-appointed judge, is ''a clear error of law that is properly
corrected at this time'' by a writ from the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in the nation's capital, the Justice Department said in
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth ''imposed significant restrictions on the president and
his closest advisers'' by saying that the Privacy Act applied to
the Executive Office of the President, and ''the need for immediate
appellate review is particularly plain,'' the Justice Department
stated.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision last week, Lamberth noted that he had ruled in
1997 that the White House needed to follow the Privacy Act, just
nine months before Clinton and his White House lawyers released the
letters Willey wrote to the president.
</P>
<P>
   In its court papers, the Justice Department said Lamberth
committed a ''significant error'' by treating his 1997 decision as
''a binding ruling'' that was ''non-appealable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A single district court's statement on an issue of law does
not make the executive branch's reasonable understanding of the law
unreasonable, much less criminal,'' said the Justice Department
filing signed by department lawyers Mark Stern and Michael Rab.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Lamberth had written that ''the White House and
president were aware that they were subject to the Privacy Act, and
yet chose to violate its provisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth's ruling came in a lawsuit by Reagan and Bush
administration appointees over the Clinton White House's gathering
of hundreds of FBI background files on Republican officials. The
judge gave the conservative group Judicial Watch, which is
representing the former officials, wide latitude in exploring
whether the White House routinely gathered and released damaging
information about opponents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
