<HEADLINE> Ex-Russian Official Released  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Former Justice Minister Valentin Kovalyov,
arrested more than a year ago on charges of embezzlement and
illegal possession of weapons, has been released from prison, the
news agency ITAR-Tass reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalyov's case has not come to trial, but he was released
because the Prosecutor General's office has finished its
investigation and Kovalyov could not interfere with it, the news
agency said, citing law-enforcement sources.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for his trial.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalyov was ousted by then-President Boris Yeltsin in July
1997, shortly after national television news programs aired a
videotape that appeared to show him cavorting with naked women in a
Russian bathhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Media reports said the bathhouse was frequented by one of
Russia's most notorious mafia gangs, and implied that the justice
minister was linked to the mob. Some reports also suggested
possible links to a banker jailed on suspicion of embezzling
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   When arrested in February 1999, he was charged with illegally
possessing weapons and ammunition, and embezzling $50,000 from a
legal foundation he leads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
