<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Economy Grows in March  </HEADLINE>
By PETER SVENSSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With prices for energy and industrial raw
materials rising in March at their fastest rate in five years,
manufacturing executives are worrying that the added expenses may
dampen business, a private report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the higher prices, the industrial economy continued to
grow in March, at a slightly lower rate than in February, according
to the widely watched report by National Association of Purchasing
Management.
</P>
<P>
   But financial markets ignored the latest evidence of growing
inflationary pressures and economic strength in a turbulent day on
Wall Street. The Nasdaq composite index plunged to its biggest
daily point drop ever, undercut by tumbling Microsoft stock, while
the Dow industrials soared.
</P>
<P>
   Norbert J. Ore, head of the purchasing agents' survey committee,
said that ''prices are currently increasing at an alarming rate,''
with 17 of 20 industries reporting higher prices for supplies,
especially for fuel and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ''A number of respondents expressed concern that escalating
energy-related costs may slow the economy,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report stoked expectations that the Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates for a sixth time since June to cool off the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The economic news, including a government report of a sharp rise
in construction spending in February, had little impact on the
stock market. Technology shares continued a steep selloff, with
Microsoft shares plunging on the collapse of negotiations to settle
an antitrust case with the government. A federal judge ruled after
markets closed that Microsoft Corp. violated federal antitrust laws
and tried to monopolize the Web browser market.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite plummeted 349.15, or by 7.6 percent, to
4,223.68. It was the biggest one-day point drop and the
fifth-biggest daily percentage decline ever. Microsoft stock lost
about $80 billion of its market value. But the Dow industrials shot
up 300.01, or 2.7 percent, to 11,221.93.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that the five past Fed rate increases have yet
to rein in the galloping economy, construction spending rose 1.5
percent in February, the Commerce Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Led by a big jump in commercial construction, spending reached a
seasonally adjusted all-time high monthly level, at an annual rate
of $758.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The purchasing managers' index of the manufacturing economy was
at 55.8 percent in March, down from 56.9 February, but well above
the reading of 50 that indicates growth. The index measuring prices
paid for raw materials was at its highest level since February
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Tim O'Neill, chief economist at the Bank of Montreal and Harris
Bank in Toronto, said the figures indicated a ''limited, very
limited moderation'' in the economy's growth.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key here, the component that would be most focused on, is
the prices part of it,'' he said, forecasting that the Fed would
increase rates by a full percentage point this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This doesn't provide any relief from the acid indigestion that
they're feeling, this is not a Rolaids treatment for them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a contrary view, Paul Christopher, an economist at A.G.
Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis, said the price index was not as
important as it once was, and that the rising prices would not
necessarily be passed on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Producers are able to use energy a lot more efficiently than
they were the last time we had a big run-up in oil prices,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, increased productivity and new financial instruments that
allow companies to stabilize their oil costs help absorb the higher
prices, Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this report will be ammunition on the side of those on
the Fed's policy board who would advocate a continued cautious
approach,'' he said, predicting another increase of a quarter
percentage point when the Fed meets May 16.
</P>
<P>
   The report surveyed the purchasing executives at more than 350
industrial companies and is closely followed because it is one of
the first readings of the economy's strength for the just-concluded
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1713 </TRAILER>
