<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Headcount comes to prisons  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN, 
o0056nyc--
r n AM-CT--Census-Prisons ConnBjt   04-03 0711
AM-CT--Census-Prisons, Conn Bjt,690   
Headcount comes to prisons   
Eds: Jamaal, 15th graf, cq   
jcstffonflsrh
AP Photos   
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENFIELD, Conn (AP) -- Some inmates at Willard-Cybulski
Correctional Institution assumed the worst when they were awakened
early Monday morning, and checked their lockers for cigarettes and
other contraband.
</P>
<P>
   The government was coming -- but only to count the inmates. U.S.
Census workers in Connecticut fanned out to prisons, extending the
national head count to people who aren't getting their mail at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the census of prisoners began Saturday and will
continue through May 6. In Connecticut, the census on Monday was
visiting 20 prisons housing 17,000 inmates, said field operations
supervisor Herman N. Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to regional census offices to determine how they will
conduct the prisoner count. In Michigan, the agency is training
prison employees to conduct the head count, said Andy Hupp, a
census technician. The count will take place on different days at
various prisons, Hupp said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10-state region handled by the Denver office, the count
began last week, said Don Lunsford, a regional technician.
</P>
<P>
   Data collection is starting this week in Pennsylvania, Maryland
and surrounding areas, said Nunzio Cerniglia, assistant regional
census manager. Census workers have not objected to going in
prisons, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're indoors in this case,'' Cerniglia said. ''You have a
controlled environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some states rely on prison administrative records rather than an
actual count of inmates, said Bart Eaton, area manager in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut's approach of training prison staff to
distribute the census forms is common, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got woken up at 7:30 this morning. Everybody thought we
were getting shut down,'' said a Connecticut inmate named Dwight.
Prison officials allowed inmates to be identified by first names
only.
</P>
<P>
   Most prisoners filled out a short form seeking basic information
such as name, age, race and date of birth. Like the general
population, one in six prisoners were given a long form seeking
additional information such as whether the person is a veteran and
if they worked last week.
</P>
<P>
   A thick door slid open slowly, leading to a brightly lit
cafeteria where dozens of inmates wearing beige uniforms walked in
slowly to fill out the forms. Five prisoners volunteered to be
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just hope it helps toward my 15-day re-entry,'' one man joked,
meaning he hoped his sentence would be reduced for his cooperation
with the count.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of inmates refused to fill out the form Monday,
Department of Correction spokeswoman Heather Zimba said. Federal
law provides a $100 penalty for refusing to cooperate with the
census, but violations are seldom prosecuted. It was not clear
whether the Connecticut inmates would be punished.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials brought forms in 37 languages, from Arabic to
Yiddish. Spanish was a common request.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's pretty self-explanatory,'' Major Bruce Cuskovich told the
prisoners. ''Anybody have any questions so far?''
</P>
<P>
   A counselor, interpreter and other staff were present to answer
a few questions.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne, a 36-year-old inmate from New Haven, said it was
important for inmates to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to know where some of that money goes,'' Wayne said.
</P>
<P>
   Other inmates questioned the need for a formal census of people
already counted several times daily.
</P>
<P>
   ''They know where we're at,'' said Jamaal, a 23-year-old
prisoner from Hartford. ''Everything we filled out in that form
they already knew.''
</P>
<P>
   The census affects government funding for different programs and
the number of seats states receive in the U.S. House of
Representatives. It also can influence decisions such as where to
locate a veteran's hospital or additional prison housing, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's much more than counting heads,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Some prisoners objected to questions about income and race.
Dwight had a problem with a question asking whether he stays at his
residence most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not staying here,'' Dwight said. ''I've been in and out of
here a couple of times, but I don't intend to make a habit of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-03-00 1716 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
