</P>
<P>
   Construction Spending Rose in Feb.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Spending on construction projects around the
country rose 1.5 percent in February, led by a big jump in
commercial building. The Commerce Department reported today that
construction spending climbed to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of $758.7 billion, an all-time high monthly level. Meanhile, a
report that the U.S. manufacturing economy was continuing to grow
also brought a warning that prices for energy and raw materials
were going up. The National Association of Purchasing Management
said the manufacturing growth was somewhat slower than last
month's.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel To Sell Software Unit
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mattel Inc. is putting its money-losing
Learning Company division up for sale, hoping to get rid of the
burdensome software unit that led to ballooning debt and big losses
at the world's biggest toymaker. Mattel said today that it retained
the investment firm Credit Suisse First Boston Corp. to find a
buyer for the Learning Company, which it acquired last May for $3.6
billion as part of Mattel's effort to tap the growing market for
interactive toys. The Learning Company was supposed to immediately
add $50 million annually to Mattel's bottom line. Instead, it added
losses of $206 million in 1999 and led to Jill E. Barad's
resignation in February as Mattel's chairman and chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Hires GM's Hughes As COO
</P>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Louis R. Hughes was named president and
chief operating officer of the Lockheed Martin Corp. today,
succeeding Peter B. Teets, who resigned amid financial turmoil at
the defense contractor. Hughes will report to chairman and chief
executive Vance D. Coffman and will be responsible for day-to-day
operations. Coffman will focus on strategic and financial issues,
the company said. Hughes, 51, comes to Lockheed from General Motors
Corp., where he had been executive vice president and president of
the automaker's $36 billion international operations, based in
Zurich, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil To Sell Europe Gas Unit
</P>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Exxon Mobil Corp. has agreed to sell a
gas-marketing unit, Mobil Europe Gas Inc., to Duke Energy
International. Terms were not disclosed for the sale announced
today, which is subject to approval by the European Commission. The
Mobil Europe unit is a natural gas marketer based in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS Drug Given to S. Africa's Poor
</P>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. is offering to
give away an expensive AIDS drug to poor South Africans, a move
that follows a series of protests and raises hopes other
pharmaceutical companies will follow suit. The drug, Diflucan,
treats cryptococcal meningitis, a lethal brain infection that
occurs in nearly one out of 10 HIV-patients. In South Africa, the
daily dose of Diflucan costs about $15, far more than the country's
many poor can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer Purchases Polyols Business
</P>
<P>
   LEVERKUSEN, Germany (AP) -- Chemical giant Bayer Corp. has
completed the purchase of the polyols business of Lyondell Chemical
Co. for $2.45 billion in a deal that makes the German company the
world's largest producer of polyurethane raw material. With the
purchase, Bayer's polyurethane division will increase to an
estimated $2.9 billion from $2.1 billion in 1999, the company said
today.
</P>
<P>
   Rexam Buying American National Can
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Britain's Rexam PLC has agreed to buy American
National Can, the world's second-largest producer of aluminum
beverage cans, for $2.1 billion. The deal announced today completes
Rexam's three-year plan to reshape the London-based manufacturer of
cans, cartons and boxes around consumer packaging activities and
gives it a strong entry into the North American can market, said
Rolf Brjesson, Rexam chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
