<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Jumps Back Against Yen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar jumped back against the yen Monday
after the Japanese central bank intervened in markets to weaken its
currency.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar was quoted at 104.85 yen in late New York trading, up
from 102.64 yen on Friday. Its moves were less pronounced against
other currencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan once again stepped into financial markets by
buying dollars and selling yen in a bid to weaken the yen, whose
recent runups have raised alarms among Japanese financial planners.
</P>
<P>
   The bank took action after releasing its latest quarterly survey
of business sentiment which, as expected, showed a slight improved
in Japan's economic outlook. Currency traders anticipating a strong
showing in the report, known as the Tankan, had pushed the yen
higher against the dollar late last week.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese authorities have intervened in currency markets several
times this year to weaken the high yen, which can choke off profits
at Japanese exporting companies that rely on overseas sales.
</P>
<P>
   The yen did not appear to react to the political uncertainty
caused by Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar was less changed against other currencies. The euro
was changing hands at 95.91 cents, up slightly from 95.59 cents
late Friday, and the British pound edged higher to $1.5990 from
$1.5934.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 1.6488 Swiss francs, down from
1.6643, and 1.4515 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4499.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0393 German
marks, down from 2.0458; 6.8397 French francs, down from 6.8615;
and 2,018.95 Italian lire, down from 2,025.39.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
