<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Irish PM Paying Back Taxes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- A former Irish prime minister has agreed
to pay about $1.23 million in back taxes on gifts given to him
while in office, the Irish Revenue Commissioners said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement with Charles J. Haughey includes an interest
payment set at almost the same amount as gifts made in the late
1980s and early 1990s by Irish supermarket executive Ben Dunne.
Haughey acknowledged taking the money, but has said there was never
any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has been a very difficult and complex case,'' said
revenue board Chairman Dermot Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey, 74, who was Ireland's dominant politician in the 1980s,
did not comment on the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   He also has been charged with obstructing the work of a tribunal
of inquiry into payments made to politicians. If convicted, he
could face a $12,100 fine and two years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey, who led three different administrations from 1979 to
1992, enjoyed a highly publicized, lavish lifestyle while in
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
