<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Fall in T-bill Sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in Monday's auction.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department sold $8.6 billion in three-month bills
at a discount rate of 5.710 percent, down from 5.720 percent last
week. An additional $7.5 billion was sold in six-month bills at a
rate of 5.900 percent, down from 5.905 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The three-month rate was the lowest since March 6 when the bills
sold for 5.690 percent. The six-month rate was the lowest since
March 20 when the rate was 5.895.
</P>
<P>
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
-- 5.873 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,855.70 and 6.166 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,701.70.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 6.30
percent last week from 6.24 percent the previous week.
</P>
</TEXT>
