<HEADLINE> Wheat Down On Crop News; Crude Down  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wheat futures tumbled Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade as
investors backed off on earlier speculation that either drought or
a late freeze will harm the winter crop.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, cocoa and crude oil retreated.
</P>
<P>
   The winter wheat crop, which accounts for the bulk of U.S. wheat
production, broke dormancy March 1 amid major concerns that dry
soil conditions dating back to last summer would harm the crop. But
a month of on-and-off showers have steadily lessened those concerns
and kept prices from exploding.
</P>
<P>
   After rallying Friday on forecasts for cold weather in the Great
Plains this week, creating worries about freeze damage, wheat
continued its rise upward briefly on Monday. But when the momentum
slowed, commodity funds went the other way and sold off wheat
contracts in a frenzy, sending the price down 2 percent for the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Commercial grain entities feel that conditions have improved
enough and there's just enough rain in the forecast,'' said Tim
Hannagan, chief grains analyst for Alaron Trading Corp. in Chicago.
''Until a return to bone-dry conditions, nobody wants to be a buyer
in the wheat market.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 4{ cents to $2.57} a bushel; May
corn fell 1} cent to $2.34\ a bushel; July oats rose 2 cents to
$1.21 a bushel; May soybeans rose 1 cent to $5.46{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Cocoa took a beating on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa
Exchange, falling 2 percent to a one-month low as a threat by Ivory
Coast growers to withhold cocoa faded.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers in the West African nation, the world's No. 1 producer
of cocoa, said last month they would strike or hold back cocoa if
the government didn't accept and implement their sales plan. But
after a meeting of the nation's export authority ended
inconclusively, buying enthusiasm dissipated in the New York
trading pits with the situation in Ivory Coast unclear.
</P>
<P>
   May cocoa fell $16 to $784 a ton.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil slipped along with energy products in a market that
has been drifting since adjusting to OPEC's much-awaited decision a
week ago to raise production. Market-watchers said the decline was
prompted largely by news reports out of Venezuela pointing to a
possible further increase by the cartel later this year.
</P>
<P>
   May crude fell 47 cents to $26.43 a barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Among other energy commodities, May heating oil fell 1.39 cent
to 67.26 cents a gallon, May unleaded regular gasoline fell 1.43
cent to 84.16 cents a gallon and May natural gas fell .56 cent to
$2.889 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, May Brent crude from the North Sea fell 26 cents to
$24.51 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
