<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Investor's Portfolio Falls  </HEADLINE>
By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was hard for investors to find a safe haven during the first
quarter, even if they diversified their holdings to protect against
the stock market's volatility.
</P>
<P>
   A sample small investors portfolio tracked by The Associated
Press had a mixture of widely held stocks and mutual funds, but big
declines in Coca-Cola and Wal-Mart as well as the risky Internet
stock eToys meant the portfolio suffered a 6.9 percent loss during
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks were pummeled the first three months of the
year amid concerns that rising interest rates would do the greatest
damage to profits of big manufacturers like Coke, whose stock fell
19.4 percent, and retailers like Wal-Mart, whose stock dropped 18.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wal-Mart and Coke are components of the Dow Jones
industrials, which ended the quarter down 5 percent after having
been off nearly 15 percent on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   But another Dow component, IBM was one of the portfolio's few
real winners, rising 9.4 percent for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth stock in the portfolio, eToys, provided ample proof
that Internet stocks are very risky. EToys, which looked like a
good bet when it was added to the portfolio at the end of the third
quarter, lost nearly two-thirds of its value during the first three
months of this year. The stock is now down nearly 87 percent since
Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Because this portfolio is relatively conservative -- apart from
the gamble on eToys -- it missed out on the Nasdaq's big gains
during the quarter. Although high-tech stocks and Internet issues
gave back some of their gains at the end of March, the Nasdaq was
still up more than 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio, which also includes four mutual funds, was valued
at $25,299.85 at its inception in Oct. 23, 1997. It was worth
$38,601.19 as of March 31, for a gain of 52.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, the Dow has risen 39.2 percent, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index has gained 57.6 percent and the Nasdaq composite
index, powered by high-tech and Internet stocks, has soared more
than 173 percent. So the portfolio is running slightly behind the
broad market during the past 2{ years.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds helped cushion the portfolio in the first quarter,
as the Vanguard Index Trust 500 Portfolio fund, which reflects the
performance of the S&AMP;P 500, matched the index's 2 percent gain. The
T. Rowe Price U.S. Treasury Long-Term Fund picked up 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Pacific Growth Fund, which had
big gains the previous two quarters, leveled off as Japan's economy
slipped back into recession at the end of 1999. The Morgan Stanley
fund rose about 1 percent for the quarter, offsetting a less than 1
percent drop in the Legg Mason Value Trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1745 </TRAILER>
