<HEADLINE> Aurora Names CEO, Restates Earnings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Aurora Foods Inc., owner of such well-known
brands as Duncan Hines and Aunt Jemima, named a new chief executive
Monday and restated its earnings for 1998 and 1999 based on an
investigation into its accounting practices.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora said James T. Smith, a former executive at food company
ConAgra, would be its CEO and president. It also named Christopher
T. Sortwell, a former executive with the brewer The Stroh Cos., as
executive vice president and chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   In February, four executives including the CEO and CFO at Aurora
resigned as the company said it would launch an investigation into
its internal accounting practices, chiefly over how it accounted
for payments for retail promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Monday it has reduced its earnings by $43.3
million for the first three quarters of 1999 and reduced by $38.3
million its 1998 third and fourth quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   That left it with a net loss for 1999 of $4.4 million, or seven
cents a share, compared to losses of $69.1 million, or $1.29 a
share, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In trading at 4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange, Aurora
Foods shares rose 37{ cents, or 12.5 percent, to $3.37{.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman and chief executive Ian R. Wilson, vice chairman James
B. Ardrey, executive vice president Ray Chung and chief financial
officer M. Laurie Cummings all resigned in February.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, Aurora has grown by acquiring well-known,
but weak brands and revitalizing them with marketing support,
expanded distribution, and new product development. It recently
moved its headquarters to St. Louis from San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In restating its earnings, Aurora also said net sales rose to a
revised $995.4 million in 1999, up from restated sales of $784.6
million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''The restatement closes a disappointing chapter for the
company,'' said Richard C. Dresdale, Aurora's acting chairman. ''We
have expended considerable effort and resources to ensure that the
company's financial reporting process and business practices adhere
to the highest standards going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The accounting practices under investigation related primarily
to trade promotion expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora's brands include Mrs. Butterworth's pancake mix, Log
Cabin syrup, Chef's Choice frozen meals, Celeste frozen pizza and
Van de Kamp's frozen seafood. In September 1999, Aurora acquired
Lender's Bagels from Kellogg's.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Aurora Foods site: http://www.aurorafoods.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
