<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Preparing for Withdrawal  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Preparations for an Israeli withdrawal of
troops from southern Lebanon are beginning, as leaders discuss the
use of an international peacekeeping force for a peaceful pullout,
U.S. officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has conferred with U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan and Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy will meet with Annan in Geneva on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Israel would prefer a pullout be part of
an overall agreement with Syria and Lebanon. But U.S. efforts to
revive Israeli negotiations with Syria have not succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ball of this negotiation is squarely in Syria's court to
respond to the serious proposals the Israelis put forward,'' State
Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has not revised its stand on major issues since President
Hafez Assad met with President Clinton in Geneva, Switzerland,
March 26, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   At that summit, Assad demanded recovery of all territory Syria
lost to Israel in its defeat in the 1967 Mideast war. Clinton said
last Tuesday Israel had made a ''very significant'' offer but that
Assad had not given him a basis for reopening the negotiations that
broke down in mid-January in Shepherdstown, W. Va.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has said he
intends to go ahead with a withdrawal of troops from a buffer zone
in southern Lebanon in July.
</P>
<P>
   And, Rubin said, Albright had spoke by telephone to Annan about
the situation, while Israeli sources said Levy would meet with the
U.N. chief in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is hoping for an orderly withdrawal from southern
Lebanon, where Hezbollah guerrillas have attacked Israeli troops.
The troops and Lebanese allies in the enclave have shielded towns
in northern Israel from cross-border attack.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary diplomacy centers on how to secure the border so
it is not used for attacks on departing Israeli soldiers and
Israeli towns. This could involve deploying an international
peacekeeping force at the border.
</P>
<P>
   On a related front, Rubin said Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators would resume talks at Bolling Air Force Base here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under discussion are the future of Jerusalem and Palestinian
demands for a state including part of the city as its capital.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is offering territory to both
Syria and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In Syria's case, it is surrender by Israel of most of the Golan
Heights, which Israel captured in 1967. In the Palestinians' case,
it involves turning over chunks of the West Bank, including land
near Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, is due here in late April
for a meeting with President Clinton. Clinton publicly has endorsed
Palestinian ''aspirations'' and sidetracked the pledge he made
while campaigning for the White House in 1992 to recognize
Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the Clinton-Arafat meeting would focus on how to
speed up negotiations for an agreement between the Palestinians and
Israel by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rubin said the talks at Bolling would be ''intensive,
substantive'' and that ''it's a little early to speculate on
exactly what will be happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 1804 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
