<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Tosses Out Yale Intern Award  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court has thrown out
$12.2 million in damages awarded to a former Yale intern who was
infected with the AIDS virus during medical training.
</P>
<P>
   The court on Friday ordered a new trial and said the judge who
presided over the original trial had improperly blocked Yale
University's effort to present evidence it is immune from such
suits under worker compensation laws.
</P>
<P>
   The high court also ruled that the verdict against Yale was
flawed because the judge neglected to instruct the jury that it had
to make a decision based on expert testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who sued under the pseudonym Jane Doe, had accused
the school of negligence. She said the school did not properly
train or supervise her when she was ordered to insert a blood line
into the arm of an AIDS patient.
</P>
<P>
   Doe was 25 when she pricked herself in August 1988, just seven
weeks into her internship at Yale-New Haven Hospital. Six weeks
later, she tested positive for the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   When an employee is injured on the job, by law they
automatically receive worker's compensation but cannot sue their
employer. Doe was an employee of the hospital at the time, and
received worker's comp.
</P>
<P>
   Yale's attorney had argued before the high court that the
university had a joint venture agreement with the hospital, making
it Doe's employer.
</P>
<P>
   Yale spokesman Tom Conroy said the university was pleased with
the decision and was looking ahead to a retrial. He said the
university still plans to claim it is immune from the suit under
worker's compensation law.
</P>
<P>
   Doe, who was never identified publicly, is now practicing at an
undisclosed location. She has not developed full-blown AIDS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
