<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Explore 'New Economy'  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With an assist from Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan, President Clinton will convene a daylong White
House conference on Wednesday on the ''New Economy,'' exploring
such issues as how to narrow the gap between the haves and have
nots.
</P>
<P>
   The conference will feature economists and other experts, chief
executives from major corporations and union officials to discuss
what Clinton earlier this year called the ''big cutting-edge
economic issues still before us.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan will address an afternoon session on the topic,
''Technology and its Impact on the Economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the head of the president's National Economic
Council, said that the administration had made a major effort to
make sure that the conference included participants with a wide
range of views to generate a lively discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to raise the toughest issues even if that means
allowing people to offer differing views to challenge our
assumptions,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   The first panel will explore the question, ''Is the 'New
Economy' rewriting the rules on productivity and the business
cycle?''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Baily, chairman of the president's Council of Economic
Advisers, said that the administration felt it important to hear
experts' views on the on-going debate over just how much of the
current upturn in productivity will last.
</P>
<P>
   The second panel is entitled, ''Closing the global divide,
strategies on health, education and the environment'' and the final
panel of the day will look at the question, ''Can 'New Economy'
tools empower civil society and government.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the issues scheduled to be addressed at the White House
conference were raised by protesters last December in Seattle, who
disrupted meetings of the World Trade Organization to highlight
their complaints that the poor in many nations were being left
behind in the current global economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   The White House conference will occur a week before many of the
Seattle protest groups are scheduled to stage demonstrations in
conjunction with the spring meetings in Washington of the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Sung Won Sohn, an economist at Wells Fargo in Minneapolis and
one of those invited to participate in the White House conference,
said while the administration may have had the demonstrators in
mind when it scheduled its conference, the issues being raised were
important ones.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology is not only creating wealth, it is also creating
economic cleavages,'' Sohn said. ''It is not just a question of the
rich getting richer. In some cases, the poor are becoming worse
off. They are getting pushed out.''
</P>
<P>
   The format of the White House economic conference, in Clinton's
last year as president, will be similar to a conference he held in
December, 1992, before his inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   He invited top economists and corporate executives to Little
Rock, Ark., for two days of discussions on what could be done to
address ways to strengthen the weak recovery from the 1990-91
recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
