<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soldiers' Training Found Deficient  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon needs to do better job of
training soldiers who may be exposed to depleted uranium, a toxin
blamed by some for Gulf War ailments, congressional investigators
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the state of the training program, the General
Accounting Office said it was unable to determine whether Marine
and Army troops were instructed on how to deal with the contaminant
before the deployment to Kosovo, where there is a possibility of
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Rostker, undersecretary of defense for personnel,
acknowledged in a letter to the GAO, Congress' investigative arm,
that training ''continues to fall short of the department's
requirements and expectations'' and said he was pointing out the
problems to the heads of the services.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lane Evans, ranking Democratic member of the House Veterans
Affairs Committee, chided the Defense Department, saying the report
showed the Pentagon had ''failed our soldiers'' on the health
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report released Monday was to assess what is known about
the health effects of exposure to depleted uranium, whether
veterans were having problems with a Pentagon medical screening
program related to it and how training was progressing.
</P>
<P>
   The Persian Gulf War marked the first battlefield use of
armor-piercing munitions using depleted uranium-coated shells and
bombs. On impact, the shells create airborne dust.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 30,000 veterans of the war have complained of mysterious
maladies such as fatigue, joint pain and memory loss they contend
are related to service in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO said in its report that the ''scientific understanding
of depleted uranium's effects on health is still evolving.'' It
noted two reviews concluded it is unlikely that inhaling or
ingesting it causes radiation or cancer. It also noted that several
more studies are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have a clear understanding of the possible health
effects ... and must do more research to get there,'' Rep. Bob
Filner, a California Democrat also on the Veterans Committee, said
in a joint statement with Evans.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the GAO had brought training problems to the
Army's attention as far back as 1993 and recommended at that time
that the services give training on depleted uranium to all military
member who may be exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that exposure to the low-level radioactive metal
should be kept ''as low as reasonably possible,'' the report said
the services ''need to do more to ensure that service members
receive safety training on how to properly operate in a depleted
uranium-contaminated battlefield.''
</P>
<P>
   It said its review in recent months of training at 17 Army units
showed that training was not given to all troops for various
reasons, such as unavailability of materials or absence from their
units of service members during training.
</P>
<P>
   ''Furthermore, because neither the Army nor Marine Corps monitor
depleted uranium training for deployments,'' the report said,
''they were unable to tell us whether troops who recently deployed
to Kosovo, where depleted uranium munitions were used, had received
... training.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force requires the training for everyone subject to
deployment, it said, and the Navy targets for its program personnel
most likely to encounter the contaminant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
