<HEADLINE> House OKs Gold Medal for Reagans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Monday to award the
Congressional Gold Medal to former President Reagan and first lady
Nancy Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution praised Reagan, president from 1981-1989, for his
leadership in restoring optimism to the nation and bringing an end
to the Cold War. Mrs. Reagan was recognized for her efforts to curb
alcohol and drug abuse among the nation's youth. The bill still
needs Senate action.
</P>
<P>
   ''If today's historians looking back at the end of the 20th
century get it right, they will surely say that Ronald Reagan more
than any other person helped to restore the American dream,'' said
Rep. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Gibbons, R-Nevada, a chief sponsor, said the medal
was ''the most distinguished form of recognition that Congress can
bestow.'' He said it was a ''fitting tribute to the dedication and
service Ronald and Nancy Reagan have given our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The one Democrat who spoke, John LaFalce of New York, remembered
Reagan, now 89 and suffering from Alzheimer's disease, ''for being
such a person of good will toward all.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he hoped the next Congress would also consider
''honoring the work of our present president and first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was not unanimous, however: seven Democrats and GOP
Rep. Ron Paul of Texas voted against awarding the medal and Rep.
Luis Gutierrez, D-Ill., voted present.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 3591.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://www.thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
