<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate committee questions costs of regulations as gas prices rise  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- In an effort to lower the price of
gasoline, the chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee said Monday
he will introduce a bill to allow New Jersey drivers to pump their
own gas.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gerald Cardinale, R-Bergen, said after a committee hearing
that he'd like to see the state's ban on self-serve gasoline
repealed. New Jersey and Oregon are the only states that require
that gasoline be pumped by a gas station attendant.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline industry representativese told members of the commerce
committee that rising crude oil prices are affecting the price at
the pump, but that state and federal regulations, including New
Jersey's mandate that only service station employees pump gas, also
drive up the price.
</P>
<P>
   Full-serve adds as much as 5 cents a gallon, according to the
New Jersey Petroleum Council.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is an absurdity, an absolute absurdity,'' said Cardinale.
</P>
<P>
   The committee had asked gas and oil suppliers to testify about
why the price of home heating oil nearly doubled in recent months
and why a gallon of gasoline hovers close to $2.
</P>
<P>
   Senators got answers: everything from the number of days that
refineries were shut down for repairs to the precarious details of
the energy futures markets.
</P>
<P>
   But when oil industry spokesmen turned the talk to the cost of
regulations, they got attention from the panel.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government mandate for full service costs New Jersey
residents several hundred million dollars alone,'' said Jim Benton,
executive director of the New Jersey Petroleum Council.
</P>
<P>
   That translates to anywhere from 3 cents to 5 cents per gallon,
Benton said, citing a 1988 Federal Trade Commission report and a
1998 Rutgers University study.
</P>
<P>
   ''The option of self serve is one of the options this committee
could make,'' Benton said, saying it and tax relief are likely the
only tools available to a state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinale said he wants to see cost impact studies, for not only
the full-serve rule, but other regulations imposed by the state.
Consumers have a right to know how much ''perfection'' costs them
when it comes to environmental safeguards, Cardinale said.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one wants to go back to the day when we had smokestacks
spewing out all sorts of noxious stuff,'' Cardinale said. But there
is a rising cost to go from ''90 percent clean to 91 percent,'' the
senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with that information, the Legislature could ''ease some
of the regulations that are not cost-effective,'' Cardinale said,
and that savings could be ''used to aid consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone on the committee was warm to the idea of
repealing state environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The committee hearing was supposed to be on what caused this
fuel ''crisis'' and how it can be prevented, Sen. Gary Furnari,
D-Essex, said.
</P>
<P>
   The self-serve ban ''has nothing whatsoever to do with why we're
here today,'' Furnari said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
