<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State police chief promotes 300 troopers, some with disciplineissues  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EWING, N.J. (AP) -- State Police Superintendent Col. Carson
Dunbar said Monday he is promoting 300 troopers before the agency
overhauls the method used to upgrade officers, a system criticized
by the attorney general after allegations of racial profiling were
made public.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the troopers promoted this week have been named in
internal affairs investigations, Dunbar said. But he said he and
Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr. personally reviewed all of
those promotions.
</P>
<P>
   These promotions, Dunbar said, will double the number of women
and minorities who hold the rank of lieutenant, the highest office
now held by a nonwhite male, with the exception of Dunbar.
</P>
<P>
   And by June, all of the captains supervising State Police road
patrols will be replaced, he said. The current captains will all
have either retired or left the job.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar said he ordered the promotions now because it could be at
least two years before any changes in the system take effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we're rebuilding, while we're improving, the problem is
we don't really have any time to stop. Our investigations keep
going on,'' Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers were told of the promotions Monday. They take effect
Friday. Many have been serving in these positions without the
accompanying rank for years, Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   In a review of State Police procedures last year, the attorney
general challenged the promotions practice, which relied primarily
on seniority. No tests were given, and in many cases, candidates
were not interviewed for the posts.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar now is considering instituting standardized tests for
applicants, according to a memo he shared with reporters Monday.
The superintendent also wants five people to be interviewed for
every captain's post. And supervisors must say in writing why they
choose candidates, Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever I do, I have to make sure I do it fairly. I will not
promote people just to be promoted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar said approximately 325 troopers were scheduled to be
promoted. But roughly 60 were the subject of an internal
investigation, he said. All investigation files were reviewed,
Dunbar said, before he decided to promote about half of those
troopers who were investigated.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent would not say what the accusations against
those officers were or if any of them were involved in racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are issues that touch on that,'' said Dunbar, who
declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer said this ''individualized'' evaluation, where records
for all of those officers were reviewed, was the only ''equitable''
way to make the promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people that did get promoted are worthy individuals,''
Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers who were not promoted are not necessarily guilty of any
charge, Dunbar said, adding that in some cases, investigations were
not completed.
</P>
<P>
   If troopers were promoted who are later found guilty of some
infractions, Dunbar said they will be removed from their new posts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to be able to stand behind my supervisors,'' he said.
''If I am wrong, and I am proven wrong, I will remove those
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of minorities and women promoted in this round is
approximately the same as those in the state police ranks -- about
17 percent, Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The minorities and females that came in now reflects their
seniority levels where they are passing into these jobs,'' Dunbar
said. In the next round of promotions, that many more women and
minorities will be eligible for higher ranks, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-03-00 1912 </TRAILER>
