<DOCNO> APW20000403.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Torricelli backs up Corzine's apology; Corzine exposes threats  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli appeared with
Democratic candidate Jon Corzine at a news conference laden with TV
cameras Monday to vouch for his lack of prejudice against Americans
of Italian descent.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, who is running against former Gov. Jim Florio for the
nomination for U.S. Senate, apologized last week after jokes
linking Italians to the mob were attributed to him.
</P>
<P>
   Florio has condemned Corzine for the jokes, saying he considered
them insulting to all Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine called the news conference to denounce what he called
outrageous attempts by an official in an Italian-American group,
Michael Cino, to get a staff job by allegedly threatening to make
public more ''dirt'' about him.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli joined Corzine in condemning dirty political tactics.
But Corzine did not say that Florio was behind Cino's alleged
threats, saying, ''I have no reason to suspect that whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same question, Torricelli said, ''I hope it really is one
man. That remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   By his appearance at a Newark hotel Monday, and with his flowing
praise for Corzine's character and qualifications, Torricelli gave
Corzine his tacit endorsement in the race for the Democratic
nomination to be decided in the June 6 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli has been coy on endorsing Corzine, limiting his
comments to confirmation that he and Corzine have been friends for
years. Torricelli added to this Monday by saying he encouraged the
former Wall Street executive to run for office when U.S. Sen. Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., announced his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I confess that when Frank Lautenberg announced his retirement,
I suggested to Jon that he consider (running), because I genuinely
believe that he would be an extraordinary United States senator,''
Torricelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg has formally endorsed Corzine in the primary, but
Torricelli heads the Democratic party's national campaign for the
U.S. Senate and so he said he was not supposed to make
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have in every state in the nation had a studied
neutrality,'' said Torricelli. ''There is some need in New Jersey,
however, to be heard on special occasions. This is one of those
occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio said he would hold Torricelli to his promise that he
would make no endorsement in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is for everyone to make their own assessment. All I know is
someone shook my hand and said they were going to be neutral, and I
am relying on that,'' Florio said. ''If somebody tells you
something, they give you their word, you have to rely on it. He is
a United States senator, after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said Cino has made threats to his staff and his wife,
Joanne, that he would reveal more dirt if staff did not agree to
meet with him promptly. Cino did not return telephone message left
Monday with the organization, the Columbus Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Alfano, head of the Italian-American One Voice Committee,
issued the news statement last week that triggered the controversy,
charging that Corzine had made ethnic jokes during meetings with
Italian Americans. Alfano said Monday he did not know who Cino was
and that Cino was not the source of information about Corzine's
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano, in his news statement, said Corzine quipped to an
Italian-American contractor, ''Oh, you make cement shoes.'' Then,
on another occasion, Alfano reported that Corzine had suggested to
a group of Italian-Americans he was meeting that they needed a
Jewish lawyer to keep them out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said Corzine's claims of being subject to dirty politics
by Cino ''does not detract from the event which precipitated this
whole experience in the past week, which is the willingness to make
derogatory comments about a whole classification of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said, ''They were unfortunate comments, an attempt at
humor from a good and decent man who doesn't have a mean bone in
his body, who has never evidenced prejudice against anybody. I
consider this matter over.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Corzine continues to insist that he does not
recall making the wisecracks, for which he promptly offered an
apology to anyone who might be offended anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
