<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Gave $334,000 To Charity in '98  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush and his wife donated $334,000
to charity in 1998, the same year he sold his interest in the Texas
Rangers baseball team. Al Gore and his wife gave away a little more
than $15,000 in 1998, but it was a larger share of their taxable
income.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores' contributions amounted to almost 7 percent of their
1998 taxable income of about $224,000, while the Bushes' donations
represented just under 2 percent of their taxable income of $18.4
million. Bush got more than $14 million when he sold his interest
in the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor who has urged support for faith-based
organizations during his Republican presidential campaign, has
donated sums ranging from $31,290 in 1993 to $9,178 in 1995,
according to records of his charitable giving the campaign released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The largest Bush contributions were to Methodist churches, as
well as the United Way, various foundations and medical causes, and
the George Bush Presidential Library in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Bush gave $150,000 to Southern Methodist University,
the alma mater of his wife Laura, on her behalf. They also gave
$15,000 to a breast cancer foundation, $35,000 to a women's shelter
and $5,000 apiece to the Red Cross and Big Brothers-Big Sisters,
among their other gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Bush has outlined a bold proposal to encourage an
outpouring of giving in America by reaching out to faith-based
groups, charities, community organizations that have a proven
record of helping those in need,'' said campaign spokesman Scott
McClellan. ''The governor and Mrs. Bush believe it is important to
give something back by volunteering their time and contributing
what they feel comfortable giving.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his wife Tipper previously reported giving away $15,197
in 1998. A spokeswoman for the vice president did not identify the
charities, but said the beneficiaries ranged from religious
institutions and educational organizations to groups that aid the
homeless and mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush nor Gore has released their 1999 income tax
returns.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was criticized in 1998 after it was disclosed that the
couple gave $353 to charity the year before after donating $35,530
in 1996. An aide said then that charitable giving ''is something
the Gores have done when the resources were there'' and that the
1996 donations were mostly proceeds from a photographic book by
Mrs. Gore while they had no similar source of income in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Gores gave away more than $50,000 of an income of
$623,000, mostly to the University of Tennessee, to endow a chair
in memory of Gore's late sister. They were aided that year by
royalties from Gore's book on the environment, ''Earth in the
Balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore staffers defended the Gore's 1997 contributions of $353,
noting that they did not claim deductions on some church donations
and gifts of food and clothing from Mrs. Gore to the homeless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
