<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidnapped Kids Saved in Guatemala  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Authorities raided four houses in and
around Guatemala City on Monday, recovering four babies they say
had been kidnapped and were to be sold to wealthy adoptive parents
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   While no arrests were made as part of Monday's raids, police
also searched the offices of two local lawyers thought to be
arranging the illegal adoption of the four infants by unknowing
foreign parents.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were ''preparing arrest warrants against several
individuals known to be involved,'' said prosecutor Francisco
Asensio.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's raids come less than a week after the release of a U.N.
report that found that infants here are often ''produced'' for sale
to parents in the United States. When poor mothers and prostitutes
are unwilling to give up their babies, the children are often
kidnapped by baby-selling rings.
</P>
<P>
   The report blamed often well-to-do lawyers for initiating the
illegal adoptions because, while the legal adoption of an infant to
Guatemalan parents can earn about $300 in legal fees, attorneys who
oversee adoptions to parents outside the country can make $25,000
per child.
</P>
<P>
   Police found all of babies in good health and in well-kept
homes, said Candito Breman, another prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Breman said he believed those that had been caring for the
stolen infants must have gotten word of the coming raids and fled
just minutes before police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ''Two of the mothers went with us as part of our efforts,''
Breman said. Authorities did not say if they had identified the
mothers of the other two children.
</P>
<P>
   One of the mothers who accompanied police, Esperanza Lopez,
finally laid eyes on her only daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said during her delivery, doctors gave her a ''drink that
must have been alcoholic'' that put her to sleep. When she awoke,
she told reporters Monday, her new daughter had been successfully
delivered but was nowhere to be found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
