<HEADLINE> Cubans in NJ to hold candlelight march for Elian Gonzalez  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos JAZ101-103
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) -- About 300 Cuban-Americans marched and
chanted Monday in support of the Miami family of Elian Gonzalez and
their fight to keep the 6-year-old boy in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The marchers made their way down Bergenline Avenue for about 15
blocks at rush hour chanting, ''Libertad para Elian,'' or ''Freedom
for Elian,'' and ''Down with Castro.'' Many held signs with the
boy's face on them and others leaned out their windows waving the
Cuban flag.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the march the group lit candles and held a moment
of silence in a lot across from the Cuban-American National
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson County is home to the nation's highest concentration of
Cuban-Americans outside Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was pulled from the Atlantic Ocean in November after his
mother and 10 other people drowned while fleeing Cuba. Since that
time, he has lived with relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department cleared the way Monday night for Elian's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to travel to the United States so he
can be reunited with his son, as negotiations continued between
immigration officials and the boy's relatives in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The department granted the senior Gonzalez's visa request along
with those of his wife, infant son and Elian's male cousin,
kindergarten teacher and pediatrician. The visas for the six could
be issued as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban activist Rolando Rios said before Monday's march here that
the boy belongs in the United States and said that his father
cannot be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   ''His father is being watched by Castro,'' Rios said,
reiterating charges made by Elian's Miami family: ''The kid is
afraid of him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
