<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, April 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge Rules Against Microsoft
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Humbling a proud giant of the computer age, a federal
judge ruled today that Microsoft violated U.S. antitrust laws by keeping ''an
oppressive thumb'' on competitors during the race to link Americans to the
Internet. In a sweeping verdict against the empire that Bill Gates built, U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said Microsoft violated the Sherman Act,
the same law used to crush monopolies from Standard Oil to AT&AMP;T. He concluded
that the company was guilty -- as the federal government, 19 states and the
District of Columbia had alleged in a case that began in May 1998 -- of
''unlawfully tying its Web browser'' to its Windows operating system that
dominates the computer market worldwide. Hearings are to be held on possible
punishment.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Record Drop of 349.15 on Nasdaq
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With Microsoft dragging down high-tech shares, the Nasdaq
composite index today plummeted a one-day record 349.15 points, or by 7.6
percent, to close at 4,223.68. But rising shares in financial firms pushed the
Dow industrials up 300.01 to close at 11,221.93. On the NYSE, gainers led losers
1,575-1,517. Since closing at a record high 5,048.62 on March 10, the Nasdaq has
fallen more than 16 percent, but it's still 3.8 percent above where it was on
Jan. 1. Microsoft fell 15] to 90~ as it appeared poised for harsh penalties in a
federal anti-trust suit.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Father Has Visa Approved
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Juan Miguel Gonzalez and other members of Elian Gonzalez's
family have been cleared by the State Department to travel to the United States.
The department granted the father's visa request along with those of his wife,
infant son and Elian's male cousin, kindergarten teacher and pediatrician. The
visas for the six could be issued as early as tomorrow. The Cubans' request for
22 other visas -- to Elian's classmates as well as National Assembly President
Rafael Alarcon -- is still being reviewed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Envoy Criticizes Russia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The United Nations' top human-rights official sharply
criticized Russia today for abuses in Chechnya, saying she heard ''very
harrowing'' accounts on a trip to the war-ravaged republic. ''I am very
concerned about the scale and seriousness of the allegations,'' U.N. High
Commissioner for Human Rights Mary Robinson said. ''Russia is a member of the
Council of Europe and as a very important member of the United Nations has
assumed international obligations under its national human rights law and
humanitarian law.'' The Council of Europe, the continent's leading human rights
watchdog, is to vote this week on whether to suspend Russia for rights abuses in
Chechnya.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Massachusetts Passes Gun Measures
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Massachusetts put the nation's strictest gun regulations into
effect today, using consumer-protection rules to ban cheap ''Saturday night
specials'' and require childproof locks on any gun sold in the state. The state
will contact gun manufacturers and sellers within 15 days to inform them of the
regulations, which also require safety warnings with each gun, tamper-resistant
serial numbers, and indicators on semiautomatic handguns that tell that tell if
a bullet is in the chamber.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton To Explore 'New Economy'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will convene a daylong White House
conference on Wednesday on the ''New Economy,'' exploring such issues as how to
narrow the gap between the haves and have nots. The conference will feature
economists and other experts, chief executives from major corporations and union
officials to discuss what Clinton earlier this year called the ''big
cutting-edge economic issues still before us.'' Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan will address ''Technology and its Impact on the Economy.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Delta Passenger Finds Loaded Gun
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- A passenger found a loaded gun in a bathroom sink on a
Delta Express flight today, forcing the plane to be diverted to Norfolk,
authorities said. The gun was found about 10 minutes after Flight 2395 left
Islip, N.Y., for Orlando, Fla. The plane landed in Norfolk less than an hour
later. About 50 passengers were on the Boeing 737. They were taken to the
airport fire station and interviewed by the FBI, agent Stephen Yount said.
Agents searched the plane for other weapons but didn't find any, he said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rodman Pleads Innocent To DUI Charge
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Dennis Rodman pleaded innocent today to a
misdemeanor drunken driving charge. The former NBA star's lawyer entered the
plea. Rodman was not required to be in court for the hearing, and is not
required to attend a pretrial conference May 4 at the Harbor Justice Center. The
charge stems from his arrest Dec. 22, when he allegedly drove with a
blood-alcohol level of 0.15 -- nearly twice the legal limit of 0.08.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
