<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German President Asking Forgiveness  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Germany's president on Monday began an
official visit to Greece, where he will tour a World War II
massacre site and ask Greeks' forgiveness for Nazi war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Johannes Rau was greeted by Greek president Costis
Stephanopoulos and an honor guard of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Rau's visit comes as the Supreme Court deliberates over a demand
for compensation from Germany over Nazi atrocities committed in
Greece during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Rau will visit the southern mountain town of
Kalavryta, where Nazi troops massacred 1,463 men in 1943 as a
reprisal for 81 soldiers shot by resistance fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Rau said the trip to the town was a ''symbolic visit'' aimed at
reminding Germans not to forget their past.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of civilians were executed during the 1941-44 Nazi
occupation of Greece as part of a brutal campaign to suppress
resistance fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Rau will also hold talks with Premier Costas Simitis and other
top leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
