<HEADLINE> Gore: Bad Schools an 'Emergency'  </HEADLINE>
By RUSS BYNUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Borrowing a phrase his Republican rival used a
week ago, Vice President Al Gore said Monday that Americans should
consider bad schools a ''national emergency'' -- and insisted he had
used the phrase first.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot afford to wait another day for the dramatic changes
and improvements that are needed,'' Gore said in a speech at
Morehouse College. ''We need to treat the existence of failing
schools as a national emergency. I used that phrase a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Gore and Republican George W. Bush are competing for
the title of ''Education Candidate'' as they battle for the White
House, with Gore pushing for more funding to hire teachers and
build and modernize schools and Bush taking the point on literacy.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiling his $5 billion reading program last week, Bush
described illiteracy among young students as a ''national
emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his point after a Morehouse student pressed him on why
the improvements he is proposing haven't come sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel the same sense of urgency that you feel,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he first used the ''national emergency'' phrase at
Graceland College in Lamoni, Iowa, where he delivered the
commencement address last May.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has a strong interest in computer technology,
reiterated his promise to link every classroom and library to the
Internet by the end of his first term. He also supports funding for
computer-equipped technology centers in poor communities and wants
every child to be computer literate before they start high school.
</P>
<P>
   ''Computers and the Internet have become as vital to education
in this century as a blackboard and chalk were in the last
century,'' said Gore, who was participating in a panel discussion
on the technology gap and the Internet's effect on equal
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King III, who appeared with Gore, said outside
help is needed for low-income families that don't have the time or
money to embrace the new technology on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're not able to learn to use the existing technology,
then you almost become obsolete,'' said King, the son of the late
civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also attended a $100,000-per-couple reception for the
Democratic National Committee at the Atlanta home of party donor
Larry Cooper that was expected to raise $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Gore was speaking at a Philadelphia community center
where, aides said, he would address proposals to make sure women --
homemakers and widowers, in particular -- get their fair share under
Social Security. He also was traveling to New York for a pair of
Long Island fund-raisers expected to net $300,000 for the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Raising money was interlaced throughout Gore's schedule this
week. He also was attending events in Annapolis, Md., on Wednesday,
Palm Beach, Fla., on Thursday and Ft. Lauderdale, Fla., on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, a Commerce Department report showed wide disparities
in computer ownership and access to the Internet based on race,
income and where people lived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
