<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Challenges Tuna Label  </HEADLINE>
By BOB EGELKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Environmentalists asked a federal judge
Monday to stop the Clinton administration from watering down the
nation's ''dolphin-safe'' tuna label to allow tuna caught with
dolphins that are netted and released.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to conflicting versions of scientific evidence,
U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson promised to rule soon on the
label change, the latest in a long-running legal and political
battle.
</P>
<P>
   For about a decade, tuna fleets that want a dolphin-safe label
have been prohibited from using large, encircling nets that trap
both tuna and dolphins, which swim with yellowfin tuna in the
eastern tropical Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Congress first restricted dolphin kills by U.S. tuna boats in
1972 and imposed similar requirements later on foreign fleets that
exported tuna to the United States. Past rulings by Henderson have
strengthened provisions requiring embargoes on nations that fail to
meet the standards.
</P>
<P>
   The labeling practice is scheduled to change April 11, when the
Commerce Department plans to allow tuna caught by Mexican boats to
carry a dolphin-safe label as long as observers on the boats see no
dolphins killed or injured in the encircling nets.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 law lifted a U.S. embargo on tuna caught with dolphins in
encircling nets and allowed the dolphin-safe label to apply to
those catches unless the National Marine Fisheries Service found
that the practice significantly harmed dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has split the environmental movement. Groups such as
Greenpeace and the World Wildlife Fund supported the 1997 law and
filed arguments supporting the government in the current case. The
plaintiffs include the American Society for the Prevention of
Cruelty to Animals and the Humane Society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
