<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stanford U. Names New President  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE M. PETERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Computer science pioneer John Hennessy
was named the next president of Stanford University on Monday,
promising to make life better for undergraduates while maintaining
close ties to Silicon Valley businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy, 47, has been the university's provost for the past
year. A former dean of Stanford's School of Engineering, he takes
over on Sept. 1 from Gerhard Casper, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stanford's best interests will be served by balancing the
lessons of the past with the advances of the future,'' said
Hennessy, who will oversee a $1.5 billion annual budget, 1,600
faculty members and 13,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally known and respected for his computer work,
Hennessy is credited with starting a successful Silicon Valley
company, MIPS Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is an entrepreneur. He has a technological background,''
said Ruben Barrales, president and chief executive of Joint Venture
Silicon Valley, a nonprofit community and business group. ''I think
it's good news for Stanford and for Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy was instrumental in securing a $150 million donation
last year by Netscape founder Jim Clark, a former Stanford
professor. The gift will fund a new cross-disciplinary science
center, dubbed Bio-X, which will focus on advances in biomedicine,
bioengineering and bioscience. It is scheduled to open in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
