<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
June Anderson Almquist:
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- The former Seattle Times columnist and assistant
managing editor, June Anderson Almquist, who led the way from high
society coverage to contemporary women's issues, died Sunday of
cancer. She was 75.
</P>
<P>
   Almquist was hired by the newspaper in 1951 to work in the
society department and in the late 1960s, she became women's news
editor.
</P>
<P>
   Almquist followed with articles on women's rights, birth
control, abortion, unwed mothers and unmarried couples, eventually
becoming the first woman to be named assistant managing editor of a
Seattle newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   For years she wrote a column, ''June's Journal,'' that often
reported on society events. She was one of the first two women on
the West Coast to hitch a ride with the Blue Angels, the Navy's
elite jet fighter stunt team.
</P>
<P>
   Almquist was the first woman to be elected president of the
local chapter of the Society of Professional Journalists and in
1998, she was awarded the group's highest national honor.
Curt Greene:
</P>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Curt Greene, the Lexington bloodstock
agent and former general manager of The Red Mile, died Saturday of
an apparent heart attack. He was 51.
</P>
<P>
   Greene turned the facilities at the Red Mile into a year-round
operation, holding various events besides racing. He resigned from
his post at the Lexington track in 1991, and was appointed to a
similar position at Louisville Downs.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, Greene stayed involved with the sport,
working as a bloodstock agent and harness racing consultant.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote for several national harness racing magazines and wrote
a book about the history of the Kentucky Futurity, the third leg in
the trotting triple crown.
Hans Gustav Gueterbock:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Hans Gustav Gueterbock, a retired University of
Chicago professor and one of the world's leading scholars of
languages of the ancient Middle East, died Wednesday. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   He was the Tiffany and Margaret Blake distinguished service
professor emeritus in the university's Oriental Institute and the
departments of Near Eastern languages and civilizations and
linguistics.
</P>
<P>
   Gueterbock, who joined the Oriental Institute faculty in 1949,
specialized in the Hittites, a people of the ancient Middle East.
He was also the co-editor of the Chicago Hittite Dictionary.
Sir Robert Sainsbury:
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Sir Robert Sainsbury, who helped build up the
venerable British supermarket chain that bears his family's name,
died Sunday. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Sainsbury joined the family company in 1930 and rose rapidly
through the ranks of what is now the second-largest supermarket
chain in Britain, with nearly 400 stores. He became chairman in
1967 and was made joint president in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Sainsbury also became a well-known patron of the arts. He and
his wife, Lisa, founded the Sainsbury Center for Visual Arts at the
University of East Anglia near Norwich, 100 miles northeast of
London. In 1978, Sainsbury donated his entire collection to the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Sainsbury was knighted in 1967 for services to the arts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
