<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capitals 4, Rangers 1  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH WHITE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Joe Sacco had his first two-goal game of the
season Monday night, lifting the Washington Capitals out of their
mini-slump in a come-from-behind 4-1 victory over the New York
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Sacco scored on a breakaway and during a delayed-penalty call,
both in the second period, as the Southeast Division-leading
Capitals broke a two-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Washington moved within two points of New Jersey in the race for
the top seed in the Eastern Conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Metropolit and Jeff Halpern added goals in the third
period. Adam Oates had two assists, moving him into 12th place on
the NHL career list with 893.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Nedved scored in the first period on a 5-on-3 power play
for New York, winless in seven games (0-6-1). The Rangers, who
fired general manager Neil Smith and coach John Muckler last week,
have been eliminated from playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved nearly had a second goal on a breakaway, but was stopped
in the first by a spectacular kick save by Olaf Kolzig. Kolzig, who
made 22 saves, kept the ragged Capitals in the game until Sacco's
first goal brought the team to life.
</P>
<P>
   Sacco, who had scored only once in 31 games, got the Capitals
going when he intercepted Kevin Hatcher's pass in Washington's zone
near the blue line. Sacco outraced the Rangers' converging
defensemen and put the puck above Kirk McLean's left shoulder at
12:06.
</P>
<P>
   Sacco's second came when the Capitals had an extra skater on
during a delayed penalty. The left wing found space in the right
circle and beat McLean in a crowded crease at 17:41.
</P>
<P>
   Oates threaded a nice pass from left wing to set up Metropolit
for the insurance score at 4:07 of the third. It was Metropolit's
sixth goal of the season, and third goal in two games.
</P>
<P>
   Ulf Dahlen fed Halpern in the slot to wrap up the scoring with
3:54 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved, a consistent performer in an otherwise dreadful Rangers
season, got his 42nd point in 41 games when he scored on a
one-timer from the right circle at 5:27 of the first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
