<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers 10, Expos 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- With one big swing, Eric Karros silenced the
Montreal Expos' largest opening-crowd since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Karros hit a grand slam and the Los Angeles Dodgers overcame
Vladimir Guerrero's two home runs, beating the Expos 10-4 Monday
night before 51,249 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers ace Kevin Brown (1-0) allowed three runs on Guerrero's
RBI single in the first and a two-run shot by the Expos slugger in
the fifth. Guerrero later hit a solo home run.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley also homered for Los Angeles and Gary Sheffield
added a two-run triple off Expos starter Dustin Hermanson (0-1).
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was the Expos' fourth-largest ever. New owner Jeffrey
Loria greeted fans at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles took a 6-3 lead in the seventh when Anthony Telford
walked Dodgers newcomer Shawn Green with the bases loaded and one
out. Karros homered on a 1-1 pitch from Scott Strickland for his
second career slam.
</P>
<P>
   Karros hit his first grand slam at Olympic Stadium last Aug. 11
off Telford.
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment of silence before the game for Cindy Lloyd,
the wife of Expos reliever Graeme Lloyd, who died suddenly in Palm
Beach Gardens, Fla., on Monday morning. She died at 26 in Florida
after a 14-year bout with Crohn's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed seven hits in six innings. He struck out seven and
walked one.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who signed an $84 million, six-year deal with Los Angeles
after he was acquired in a trade with Toronto last Nov. 8, went
0-for-3, with two walks and an RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Hermanson allowed five runs, though just one earned, in six
innings. The Expos committed four errors, including two by third
baseman Michael Barrett, who mishandled Devon White's grounder on
an 0-2 pitch to open the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos have led the majors in errors in each of the last two
seasons, including 160 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles and Montreal became the fifth and sixth teams to
open the current season outside of the United States, a first in
major league history. The New York Mets and Chicago Cubs opened the
season with a two-game series last week in Japan, and Toronto
played host to Kansas City earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The game was Los Angeles' first opening day outside of
the United States, and the first season opener between the Dodgers
and Expos. ... Expos 1B Lee Stevens made a diving stop of F.P.
Santangelo's sharply hit grounder for the first out of the eighth.
He then committed his first NL error on Mark Grudzielanek's two-out
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
