<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> What's Next for Japan's Gov't?  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A look at the leadership crisis facing the Japanese
government:
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSING A SUCCESSOR:
</P>
<P>
   The selection process would begin with the nomination of a new
president of the Liberal Democratic Party. The Cabinet would be
dissolved, and the Parliament would vote on the LDP nominee.
Because the LDP has more seats than any other party, its president
is guaranteed the prime ministership.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   POTENTIAL CANDIDATES:
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiro Mori, secretary-general of the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party, has emerged as the most likely successor to Obuchi. Other
possible candidates are Foreign Minister Yohei Kono and Chief
Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki, who took over as acting prime
minister on Monday. Aoki, however, is seen as more of a temporary
stand-in than a potential premier.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   PRESSING ISSUES:
</P>
<P>
   The ruling LDP is still in firm control, so no big changes were
in store on economic policies, but political stability was needed
to gain the confidence of the markets. Japan is also facing talks
this week with North Korea, volcanic eruptions in the northern part
of the country, and preparations to host the G-8 summit of
industrialized nations in July.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL COMPLICATIONS:
</P>
<P>
   Parliamentary elections must be held by October, but the
leadership crisis is likely to fuel opposition demands for a snap
vote. Obuchi's illness also came as his unwieldy three-party ruling
coalition was beginning to splinter, though the LDP still has
enough seats in Parliament to control the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 2225 </TRAILER>
