<HEADLINE> MSU Leads Fla. 43-32 at Half  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Mateen Cleaves scored 13 points in the first
half and Michigan State showed it could run with Florida, building
a 43-32 halftime lead in the NCAA championship game Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans, who slogged their way to a 53-41 victory over
Wisconsin in the semifinals, willingly turned up the throttle
against the Gators, consistently beating the full-court pressure to
set up easy baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State had 18 field goals in the first half, two more
than its total in the entire game Saturday. The Spartans were
shooting 53 percent from the field and had committed only four
turnovers against the high-pressure Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, who returned for his senior season for a chance to win
a national title, hit a pair of 3s to highlight a 14-3 run that
gave Michigan State its biggest lead, 33-20. Until Monday, Florida
had never faced a deficit of more than seven points in its previous
five tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves was 3-of-3 shooting outside the arc and 5-of-8 overall
after a 1-of-7 performance against Wisconsin. He also had plenty of
help: A.J. Granger scored 9 points, Jason Richardson and Morris
Peterson had 6 apiece, and Charlie Bell added 5.
</P>
<P>
   Udonis Haslem was leading Florida with 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, eliminated in the semifinals a year ago, was
trying to win its second national title. In 1979, the Magic
Johnson-led Spartans defeated Larry Bird and Indiana State in the
title game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson watched this game from the green-clad Michigan State
section at the RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Florida was playing in the final for the first time. The Gators
were eliminated in the semifinals in 1994, their only other trip to
the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Florida also was trying to keep alive the Southeastern
Conference's streak of winning the championship in even-numbered
years. Arkansas captured the title in 1994, while Kentucky finished
No. 1 in both 1996 and '98.
</P>
</TEXT>
