<DOCNO> APW20000403.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holocaust-Era Heroes Honored  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- During World War II, 84 diplomats from 24
countries risked their lives to issue visas and passports that
saved more than 300,000 Jews from the Holocaust. After 55 years,
the international community paid tribute Monday night to the
courage of these unsung heroes -- many who lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thanks to them some measure of hope and faith was possible --
hope for the future and faith in the creator as well as his
creatures,'' said Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel, a Holocaust survivor.
''But ... why didn't others do it?''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony in the General Assembly hall coincided with the
opening of a U.N. exhibition called ''Visas for Life: The Righteous
Diplomats,'' which runs through April 30 and features untold
stories and unpublished photographs of the 80 men and four women.
</P>
<P>
   ''At a time when evil was all around, they affirmed the enduring
power of human decency,'' New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, one of
more than a dozen speakers, told the crowd of several hundred that
included relatives of the diplomats and some of the Jews they
saved.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe there are more than 500,000 people alive today as a
result of diplomats who mostly defied the orders of their
governments to issue visas to every country in the free world,''
said Eric Saul, director of the exhibition. ''More than half of
these men were fired from the governments, dishonored, lost their
careers, their dignity -- and in some cases have yet to be honored
in their home country.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the most famous diplomat, Raoul Wallenberg of
Sweden, is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   His niece, Nane Annan, the wife of Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
recalled how her uncle issued Swedish diplomatic papers to more
than 30,000 Hungarian Jews before he was arrested by the Russians
in January 1945 and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Not a day passed that her grandmother didn't try to find him --
''I can see her gripping the phone, knuckles white from the
tension'' -- and since her grandmother's death, her mother has
continued the search, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never met him, but I know how families of disappeared
persons feel. Although he was absent, he was constantly present,''
said Mrs. Annan, who was born three months before her uncle's
arrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-03-00 2248 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
