<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Rebels Kidnap 23 Motorists  </HEADLINE>
By MARGARITA MARTINEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Leftist rebels kidnapped 23 motorists
and hampered road and river traffic in central and northern
Colombia Tuesday after calling for a transportation strike.
</P>
<P>
   National Liberation Army guerrillas also burned vehicles, blew
up a bridge and threatened to destroy river boats, the latest in a
series of attacks apparently aimed at putting pressure on the
government to allow the group a place upcoming peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The abductions occurred on a highway in northern Cesar state,
where ELN fighters set up a temporary roadblock and dragged
motorists from their vehicles into nearby mountains, said army
spokesman Capt. Edgar Ortega. Colombian rebels routinely kidnap
motorists for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The ELN, Colombia's second-largest rebel group, has been angry
over the government's decision to focus its peace strategy on
contacts with a more powerful group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia, or FARC. The ELN has waged a sabotage campaign in
recent months against the energy infrastructure, bombing power
pylons and causing blackouts over wide areas.
</P>
<P>
   Road traffic was paralyzed on the main highway connecting Bogota
and the second-largest city, Medellin, after rebels dynamited a
bridge and burned three tractor trailers.
</P>
<P>
   The ELN staged an armed occupation of the same highway for
nearly a week in February, holding hundreds of motorists as human
shields before retreating. The affected stretch of road remained
closed Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel threats against commercial and passenger boats along the
Magdalena River cut traffic by 70 percent around northeastern city
of Barrancabermeja, regional police chief Col. Jaime Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Bus and taxi traffic ground to a halt and some schools were
closed after the ELN burned three buses, Martinez added. The rebel
transport strike is scheduled to continue through Apr. 10, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brief highway blockades and sporadic vehicle burnings were also
reported in other parts of Antioquia and in the states of Bolivar,
Guajira, Cesar, and Magdalena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
