<HEADLINE> MSU's Cleaves Hurts Ankle in Final  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Michigan State star Mateen Cleaves, after
scoring 18 points, twisted his right ankle with 16:18 left in the
second half of the NCAA championship game against Florida on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves got tangled up with Florida's Teddy Dupay while driving
to the basket and rolled his right foot after putting up the shot.
The whistle already had blown for a foul behind the play, but
neither Cleaves nor Dupay could hear the call.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan State point guard crawled along the baseline,
grimacing in pain. But he was able to get to his feet and walk to
the locker room under his own power.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves returned to the bench after trainers taped up his ankle.
He told coach Tom Izzo, ''I'm OK,'' and returned to the court with
11:51 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   During his absence, Michigan State actually stretched its lead
from 50-44 to 58-50.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, a second-team All-America, missed the first 13 games of
the season after breaking the same foot.
</P>
</TEXT>
