<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000403.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell moderately Tuesday morning amid
political uncertainty in Japan. The dollar edged higher against the
yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 104.91 points,
or 0.51 percent, to 20,622.08 points in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Monday, the average closed up 389.67 points, or 1.92
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 104.94 yen in late morning, up 0.08 yen from
late Monday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of
104.85 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock exchange, traders said investors remained cautious
of the possibility that the Cabinet of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi,
who remains in a coma after suffering a stroke, will resign in a
few days.
</P>
<P>
   In a regular news conference Tuesday morning, Mikio Aoki,
Japan's chief Cabinet secretary and acting prime minister, said the
Cabinet has yet to decide whether it will resign and nominate a
successor to Obuchi. Yoshiro Mori, secretary-general of the Liberal
Democratic Party, is viewed as the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese media said the resignation of the Cabinet could happen
as early as Tuesday and a new Cabinet could be installed by the end
of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be a wait-and-see stance by investors,'' said
Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Prices started lower Tuesday on profit-taking following recent
gains. Investors in Tokyo were also discouraged by declines in U.S.
high technology stocks on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 9.00 points, or 0.52 percent, to 1,723.45.
The TOPIX closed up 26.51 points, or 1.55 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index plunged 349.15 points
to close at 4,223.68. It was the Nasdaq's worst point drop in
history, surpassing a 229-point fall on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar was higher against the yen in
narrow trading amid continued concern of another central bank
intervention to stem any drop by the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese importers and U.S. and Canadian banks were among early
players who bought the greenback after Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa reiterated his determination to be ready to take action
against the yen's excessive upsurge.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said Tuesday that Japan is
ready to take necessary action to contain disruptive foreign
exchange moves.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Bank of Japan intervened in the market to weaken
the yen, whose recent rise has alarmed Japanese financial planners.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese finance authorities have intervened several times this
year to stem gains by the yen, which make Japanese exports more
expensive overseas, and thus less competitive.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 100.36 yen, up from
100.14 yen late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell
to 1.7900 percent from Monday's finish of 1.8050 percent. Its price
rose 0.13 point to 100.94.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
