<DOCNO> APW20000403.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MSU's Peterson Stars in Title Game  </HEADLINE>
By HAL BOCK, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Morris Peterson did this for his
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Heartbroken when he learned Clara Mae Spencer died on March 25,
the Michigan State senior flew to Mississippi for her funeral, then
returned for the Final Four. He wrote her name on his sneakers, a
private memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson scored 20 points in the semifinal against Wisconsin and
then another 21 in Monday night's 89-76 win over Florida for the
national championship. He also had two rebounds, five assists and a
steal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know she is with me on the court,'' he had said last
weekend. ''I can feel her presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's performance capped a big NCAA tournament for the
fifth-year senior, who came back for this game, this night, this
national championship. He was a huge presence in the Midwest
Regional, scoring 21 points against Syracuse, 18 against Iowa State
and helping Michigan State dominate the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the funeral and his emotional return.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson was one of Michigan State's trio of Flintstones, who
grew up with Charlie Bell and Mateen Cleaves in the industrial city
of Flint, playing on concrete courts and becoming buddies.
Together, they went to East Lansing, determined to win a title.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Peterson helped Michigan State to the Final Four,
but the Spartans lost to Duke in the semifinals. He could have left
after that, but stayed for one more shot.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a matter of wanting to be around the Spartan family,''
he said. ''These guys are like brothers to me. We come from a
background where education is important. There was never any doubt.
We talked about winning a national championship together.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday night, that's exactly what they did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
