<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, April 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge Rules Against Microsoft
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge ruled Monday that Microsoft Corp. violated
U.S. antitrust laws by keeping ''an oppressive thumb'' on competitors during the
race to link Americans to the Internet -- a sweeping verdict against the empire
that Bill Gates built. U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said
Microsoft violated the Sherman Act, the same law used to crush monopolies from
Standard Oil to AT&AMP;T. He concluded that the company was guilty of ''unlawfully
tying its Web browser'' to its Windows operating system that dominates the
computer market worldwide.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Drops 349.15; Dow Up 300
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index was devastated Monday -- a victim
of the Microsoft verdict -- falling 15] to 90~ as Wall Street anticipated a
federal judge's antitrust ruling against the software company. The stampede away
from technology stocks sent investors searching for blue-chip issues, and gains
by financial, retail and drug stocks helped the Dow Jones industrials soar 300
points. The Nasdaq plunged 349.15, or 7.6 percent, to close at 4,223.68. It was
the Nasdaq's worst point drop in history.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Visa OK'd for Elian's Father
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As negotiations continued between immigration officials
and Elian Gonzalez's Miami relatives, a visa was approved for the Juan Miguel
Gonzalez to travel to the United States so he can pursue his quest to be
reunited with his son. The department also granted visa requests for his wife,
infant son and Elian's male cousin, kindergarten teacher and pediatrician. The
visas for the six could be issued as early as tomorrow.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Prime Minister in Coma
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was on life support Tuesday after a
stroke, leaving the Japanese government to grapple with a leadership crisis and
the possibility of dissolving the Cabinet and finding a successor. There was
also growing anger over the delays by the government in reporting Obuchi's
illness to the public. As Obuchi's family assembled at the Tokyo hospital where
he has been since Sunday, acting Prime Minister Mikio Aoki called a Cabinet
meeting for Tuesday amid speculation that politicians were moving quickly to
name a successor.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mass. Announces Strict Gun Laws
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Massachusetts put the nation's strictest gun regulations into
effect Monday, using consumer-protection rules to ban cheap ''Saturday night
specials'' and require childproof locks on any gun sold in the state. The state
will contact gun manufacturers and sellers within 15 days to inform them of the
regulations, which also require safety warnings with each gun, tamper-resistant
serial numbers, and indicators on semiautomatic handguns that tell if a bullet
is in the chamber. Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening predicted that within 18
months, six to 12 states will move forward on similar legislation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bosnian Arrested for War Crimes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- French NATO troops arrested the most senior
Bosnian Serb war crimes suspect to date Monday, sweeping into the Serb
stronghold of Pale in a pre-dawn raid that galvanized the crusade to bring the
architects of the Balkans' ''ethnic cleansing'' campaigns to justice. Momcilo
Krajisnik, a close ally of former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, was
arrested at his home by troops who witnesses said forced open his door.
Krajisnik is charged with every war crime on the Yugoslav tribunal's statute,
including genocide.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hail, Winds Rip Through the South
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Hail, heavy rain, high winds and tornadoes tore through
the South early Monday, ripping off roofs, tossing trees into power lines and
apparently forcing a small plane into the Gulf of Mexico. The storms struck from
Texas to Georgia, with at least one storm-related death reported in Alabama.
Damage was widespread: Roofs and power lines broke in or near dozens of cities
and towns.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell moderately on profit-taking in reaction to
recent sharp gains and political uncertainty after Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
fell into a coma after suffering a stroke. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock
Average shed 104.91 points to 20,622.08.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Michigan St. Wins NCAA Championship
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Michigan State won its second national championship as
Mateen Cleaves led the Spartans to an 89-76 victory over Florida Monday night.
Cleaves helped the Spartans build a 43-32 halftime lead by scoring 13 points,
including going 3-for-3 from 3-point range.
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS 
</P>
